<HEADLINE> U.S. Allows Direct Flights to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that it will allow direct charter flights to Cuba from New York
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
The flights will be limited to certain categories of U.S.
residents, including journalists, government officials and
once-a-year humanitarian visits to family members, State
Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the move did not represent an easing of
sanctions against Cuba, the spokesman said the practice is
consistent with the current policy of the administration and a ban
on tourism remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of the process that has been put in place for
some time where we are trying to improve people-to-people contact,
and doing it in such a way as not to provide benefit to the Cuban
regime, which is precisely what the embargo is designed to
prevent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The flights will be "only available" to travelers licensed by
the Office of Foreign Assets Control in the Treasury Department in
addition to the existing general license, he added.
</P>
<P>
On January 5, the Clinton administration authorized flights to
Cuba to improve "people-to-people" contact. Charter planes have
been flying from Miami to Camaguey and Holguin for several months.
</P>
<P>
The United States started its embargo in 1961 against Cuba
after the country's pro-American government was toppled in a
revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
