<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassies Alerted Before Bomb Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States has warned
all its embassies and consulates around the world to pay
particular attention to security ahead of the first anniversary of
the bombing of its two embassies in Africa, the State Department
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have told every one of our posts that they should be
particularly attentive during this period of time," said Assistant
Secretary of State Patrick Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
"There is often an increased danger around anniversaries of
this type," he added.
</P>
<P>
The State Department warning was issued on July 25 to all U.S.
265 embassies and consulates, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last August, two U.S. embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and in Dar
es Salaam, Tanzania, were destroyed by bombs, which killed at
least 226 people, including 12 Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
