<HEADLINE> Less-known Chinese Teenager Beats World No. 5 Qianhong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese teenager Li
Nan pulled off the biggest upset on the second day of the world table
tennis championships as she upset former Chinese and world
fourth-ranked Gotsch Qianhong in the women's singles opening round.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Li, a fast-attacker who plays in penhold grip,
handed a 20-22, 21-17, 21-16, 21-13 defeat to the fourth seeded
Qianghong who had played for the Chinese Army team and now plays for
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Both Li and Qianhong were born in northern Chinese city Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Li began to play table tennis at 7 and joined the national team in
1996. She finished fifth in the doubles event in the 1998 Chinese
national championships.
</P>
<P>
The best German table tennis trio were all Chinese. Jing
Tian-Zorner is ranked fourth in the world with Jie Schopp 11th. Both
made the second round on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
