<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Approves State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti Parliament on
Tuesday approved a 4.25 billion dinars (some 14 billion U.S.
dollars) budget for the fiscal year 1999/2000 starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was passed by a vote of 27 to 20 with one
abstention, projected state revenues at 2.224 billion dinars (some
7.339 billion dollars), and a deficit at 2.026 billion dinars
(6.685 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues were estimated at 1.761 billion dinars (5.811
billion dollars) and non-oil income at 463 million dinars (1.527
billion dollars), compared with 1.894 billion dinars (6.25 billion
dollars) and non-oil income of 550 million dinars (1.815 billion
dollars) for the past year respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, 222 million dinars (732.6 million dollars) will go
to the Fund for Future Generations, which was designed to
prepare for the time when Kuwait's oil passes its heyday.
</P>
<P>
The state's oil revenue in the new budget is calculated at a
daily output of 1.386 million barrels per day, Kuwait's current
quota within the framework of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues in the last and new budgets are calculated
at 10 dollars a barrel, down from 13 dollars in recent
years. Kuwait's crudes are currently selling at 13-15 dollars
per barrel after dropping below 7 dollars last year when
world oil prices plummeted to a ten-year low.
</P>
<P>
The 4.362 billion dinars (14.39 billion dollars) budget for
1998/99 carried a projected gross deficit of 2.163 billion
dinars (7.137 billion dollars) and a net deficit of 1.919
billion dinars (6.332 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Economists here expected an actual net deficit of 1.25
billion dinars (4.125 billion dollars) with expenditure of about
4 billion dinars (13.2 billion dollars) after spending curbs
were introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
