<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) are planning a joint campaign to prepare for the expected
flood of pilgrims at Christian sites during the millennium year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials are concerned about the overcrowding at the
most popular sites, like the Church of the Holy Sepulcher in
Jerusalem, the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem, and the
baptismal sites along the Jordan River, local daily The Jerusalem
Post said Tuesday. (BC-Israel-Palestine-Millennium)
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinians have categorically rejected an Israeli
proposal to put off the implementation of the Wye Accord and to
combine part of the agreement with the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Palestine Liberation Organization
Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas said there was no justification
for delaying troops withdrawal for several months, Voice of
Palestine radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abbas, who is also known as Abu Mazen, made the remarks in
response to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's proposal to start
the remaining two stages of troops withdrawal on October 1.
(BC-Palestine-Wye Accord)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Tuesday demanded an immediate response from
Turkey on its inquiry into air raids of Iranian border outpost and
villages two weeks ago, in which five Iranians were killed and
another 10 injured.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA),
the demand was made by Iran's ambassador to Turkey Mohammad
Hussein Lavasani, who on Monday held talks with Turkish Foreign
Ministry director general for the Middle East affairs.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said the two discussed the upcoming meeting of the
neighbors' joint security commission to be held in Ankara on
August 9-13. (BC-Iran-Turkey-Border Inquiry)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has barred seven members of a Saudi prince's
entourage from leaving the country pending investigation into two
assault charges, the prosecutor general said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Maher Abdel-Wahed said two brothers-in-law of Saudi
Prince Turki Ibn Abdul-Aziz and four of his bodyguards - two
Americans, an Austrian and a Syrian - will not be allowed to leave
the country until the investigations were completed.
</P>
<P>
A friend of the Saudi family is also not allowed to leave.
(BC-Egypt-Saudi Prince-Ban)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi will fly to Egypt on
Wednesday for talks with President Hosni Mubarak, an Egyptian
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This will be Gaddafi's first trip to Egypt since the United
Nations suspended air embargo on Libya in April, the official at
the Foreign Ministry said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The official said Gaddafi will meet with Mubarak for the
day-long talks in the Mediterranean town of Marsa Matrouh, 500
kilometers northwest of Cairo. (BC-Egypt-Libya) 
</P>
</TEXT>
