<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Stand by Promise to IMF: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe said Tuesday that it will
 rigorously implement a number of policies to achieve the
macro-economic goals contained in its letter of intent to the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa said this at a
briefing after the disbursement of 193-million-U.S. dollar
stand-by credit facility for Zimbabwe by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the money would be used to rebuild Zimbabwe's
foreign exchange reserves and put its economy back onto a sound
reform track.
</P>
<P>
The macro-economic goals as contained in the letter to the IMF
included the achievement of real gross domestic product (GDP)
growth of 12 percent in 1999, the reduction of inflation to 30
percent by the end of the year and an external current account
deficit of 6.3 percent of the GDP, which together with additional
external financing should allow gross reserves to increase to 16
months of imports by year end.
</P>
<P>
To meet these objectives, a number of policies would be
implemented including the maintenance of a tight fiscal stance and
the targeting of the budget deficit at 5.3 percent of the GDP,
which was equivalent to a primary surplus of 3.2 percent of the
GDP, Murerwa said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the minister as saying that
monetary policy and fiscal restraint would be used to contain
aggregate demand and maintain a competitive exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
New legislation to strengthen the regulation of banks which had
been passed by parliament would soon come into force and policy
guidelines to deal with distressed banks would be issued, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said that his government had no intention of imposing
widespread price controls, and that price controls on maize meal
were introduced only as temporary measures for socio-economic
reasons.
</P>
<P>
The price controls would be lifted once the situation improves
and the exchange rate stabilizes, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the projected external financing gap would be financed
through disbursements from the World Bank with 140 million dollars
and the African Development Bank with 130 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
