<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Panels Named to Probe into How UNITA Evades Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Tuesday completed the makeup of two panels in
charge of investigating how Angola's rebel UNITA have been evading
sanctions and the 15-nation body is expected to offer
recommendations on counter-measures to strengthen sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
has been blamed by the Security Council for the breakdown of a
1994 peace accord designed to end a length civil war in the
central African country and for the resumption of fighting last
December.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the two panels, which have a six-month
mandate and will probably travel widely, was approved by the
Security Council in a resolution adopted in May.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Security Council's sanctions committee,
Robert Fowler who is the Canadian ambassador to the United
Nations, said in a letter to the Council president that one
six-member panel would probe UNITA's sources of revenue, funding
and petroleum supplies that enable it to wage war.
</P>
<P>
It will be headed by Anders Mollander, who was Sweden's
ambassador to Angola from 1992 to 1995 and now deals with African
affairs in his country's foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Other members include experts from Zimbabwe, Namibia, Britain
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
One focus of the panel will be diamond trade by UNITA, which
controls a number of diamond-rich areas in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Fowler told reporters last week that UNITA was estimated to
have raised between 3 billion U.S. dollars to 4 billion U.S.
dollars through diamond sales over the past eight years and that
this sum had probably grown as a result of wise investments.
</P>
<P>
The second panel named by Fowler, comprising four experts, will
investigate the sources of UNITA's military support. It will be
headed by Col. Otisitswe Broza Tiroyamodimo of Botswana, a deputy
brigade commander who formerly served with U.N. peacekeeping force
in Mozambique. The other three members are from South Africa,
Switzerland and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mollander will serve as chairman of the entire 10-member group
and Tiroyamodimo will be vice-chairman.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has claimed hundreds of lives over more than two
decades and the United Nations estimates that 1.6 million Angolans
are dispatched out of a population of about 11 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
