<HEADLINE> S. Africa Condemns Namibian Rebel Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Tuesday
condemned "in the strongest terms" the killing of civilians in
Namibia's Caprivi Strip.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on behalf of the South African
government, Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma gave her full support
to a united Namibia and its government's efforts at resolving the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
She told state television that South Africa would condemn any
violent actions against a legitimate, democratic government.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between secessionist rebels and the government forces
erupted after rebels attacked the police station in Katima Mulilo
and a nearby airport in the wee hours of Monday in Namibia. The
rebels once occupied the state- owned radio offices in the town,
which was later recovered by police and the army.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma Monday declared an indefinite
state of emergency in the area as government forces are carrying
out a mop-up operation.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the town remained tense Tuesday afternoon as
occasional automatic gunfire could be heard, according to South
African state television, the SABC.
</P>
<P>
The television also said efforts were being made to evacuate
foreign nationals in the region as a new attack by the rebels
could not be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
The exact number of casualties in Monday's fighting could not
be known, but there are speculations that up to 20 people might
have died.
</P>
<P>
Five rebels, five policemen and three soldiers were confirmed
dead.
</P>
<P>
The Caprivi Strip is a stretch of land sandwiched by Angola,
Zambia, Zimbabwe and Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
