<HEADLINE> UK Leading Banks Plan "Sofa Banking" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON August 3 (Xinhua) - Banking giant HSBC and Abbey
National announced Tuesday that they are planning services for
customers to manage their finances using their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
The new services are the latest in a series of announcements by
major banks that signal a move away from traditional
over-the-counter service to "remote" banking, via the telephone,
the internet and now television.
</P>
<P>
Abbey National's so-called "sofa Banking" interactive
television service will enable armchair customers to review
products, order literature and calculate their loan repayments
simply by using the remote control.
</P>
<P>
An HSBC spokeswoman said: "Customers and non customers will
soon be able to buy financial products off the shelf while
enjoying the comfort of their own sofas."
</P>
<P>
The interactive TV service will initially be available to
customers with Sky Digital only, but will eventually appear on all
digital services, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Part of the service will be one stop shop for financial
products, such as insurance. There will also be facilities for
customers to access accounts, pay bills and transfer cash, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Ambrose McGinn, Abbey National e-commerce director, said:
"Television banking is a global first, and we think its potential
is enormous." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
