<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission in East Timor to Stay One Month Longer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Tuesday authorized the U.N. Mission in East
Timor (UNAMET) to stay one month longer until September 30.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a council meeting following U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's request for UNAMET's extension last
week.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been mandated with the mission to
organize and conduct a vote in East Timor on its future -- to
enjoy special autonomy within Indonesia or to go independent.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has seen East Timor of 800,000 inhabitants as a
non-self-governing territory administered by Indonesia, which
annexed it in 1976, ending Portugal's nearly 400-year colonial
rule.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N. agreed on May 5 to conduct a
ballot or popular consultation on East Timor's status.
</P>
<P>
The original voting date was set for August 8. Due to security
reasons and logistics preparations, it was first postponed to
August 21 or 22.
</P>
<P>
Annan delayed the ballot again last week until August 30.
Subsequently, he put off UNAMET by one month from the end of
August till the end of September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
