<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Supply Cut to Israeli Cities Over Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- After the negotiations with the
Finance Ministry over wage increase broke up, Israeli water
workers Tuesday cut off the water supply to dozens of cities
around the country.
</P>
<P>
The shutoffs were first imposed by Mekorot Water Company's
workers overnight on a number of cities, including the coastal
cities of Tel Aviv and Ashkelon.
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv municipality water control headquarters were
reportedly inundated with complaints by disgruntled citizens, who
woke up in the morning only to find the water had been cut off.
</P>
<P>
Since a labor court had ordered that any shutoffs could not be
allowed to go on for more than four consecutive hours out of every
day, Mekorot workers resumed water supply to these cities hours
later.
</P>
<P>
Then, the workers continued their strike Tuesday afternoon by
cutting off water to other cities, including Jerusalem, for hours.
</P>
<P>
However, Mekorot workers council chairman Meir El-Ezra said on
Tuesday that the staff were trying not to cut water supply to
hospitals and Israel Defense Force camps.
</P>
<P>
Mekorot workers are demanding for a wage rise of 3 percent over
the next two years. They are also protesting government plans to
privatize the water company, which they say would put hundreds of
people out of work.
</P>
<P>
But Finance Ministry officials said that the wages of Mekorot
staff had posted a real 15 percent increase in the last five
years, and that they are currently demanding another irrational
wage increase, exploiting their control on the country's water
taps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
