<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Index Rises In June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The composite index of leading
economic indicators rose 0.3 percent in June, pointing to
continuation of the expansion through early 2000, the Conference
Board, a prominent research group, said in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the index stands at 107.7 in June, up from
107.4 in May, posting increases in eight of the past nine month.
</P>
<P>
"The (economic) expansion is firmly on track," said Michael
Boldin, director of business cycle research at the Conference
Board. "But because of concerns about if and when the Federal
Reserve will tighten to fight inflation, some volatility can be
expected in the second half of 1999."
</P>
<P>
The report said seven of the 10 indicators that make up the
leading index rose in June. The most significant increases are
manufacturers' new orders of consumer goods and materials, money
supply in 1992 dollars and interest rates spread, it added.
</P>
<P>
The most significant negative contributor to the composite
leading index in June is manufacturers' new orders of nondefense
capital goods, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that during the six-month span through June, the
leading index rose 1.2 percent, and seven of the 10 components
advanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
