<HEADLINE> S. African Currency Ends Softer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The South African currency
rand ended softer Tuesday against the U.S. dollar in a range bound
session.
</P>
<P>
The session was characterized by players buying and selling
dollars on the bottom and top side of the range. The rand traded
in a narrow range of 6.1840 to 6.2200.
</P>
<P>
The rand was last quoted at 6.1930 per dollar from a previous
close of 6. 1900. The rand weakened to an intra-day worst level
of 6.2220 before midday, but traded below the 6.2000 psychological
level for most of the day.
</P>
<P>
The rand market showed signs of recovery late in the afternoon
and that that could be a sign of a slight correction.
</P>
<P>
The local market developed jitters Monday after the Reserve
Bank governor-designate, Tito Mboweni, commented that the central
bank would not intervene in the currency market. Mboweni is to
take over the reigns at the bank on August 10.
</P>
<P>
Dealers expected a slight firming in the rand after Mboweni's
inauguration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
