<HEADLINE> Members of Saudi Prince's Entourage Barred from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has barred seven members of a
Saudi prince's entourage from leaving the country pending
investigation into two assault charges, the prosecutor general
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Maher Abdel-Wahed said two brothers-in-law of Saudi
Prince Turki Ibn Abdul-Aziz and four of his bodyguards - two
Americans, an Austrian and a Syrian - will not be allowed to leave
the country until the investigations were completed.
</P>
<P>
A friend of the Saudi family is also not allowed to leave.
</P>
<P>
The move was the harshest one by the Egyptian authorities
against the prince and his entourage since 1983 when they moved
into the top floors of the Ramsis Hilton Hotel in Cairo after
falling out with his brother, King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
In June, an Egyptian police officer accused the prince's son,
the two in-laws, their Saudi friend and three bodyguards of
assaulting him in a cafeteria of the hotel while he was off-duty.
</P>
<P>
But the prince's son, Prince Abdul-Rahman, has not been banned
from leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
Also, a cook who had gone to the prince in search of a job,
claimed last month that one of the American bodyguards had
assaulted him in a hotel elevator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
