<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New ITTF President Faces Uphill Battle  By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The 40mm ball proposal
was overruled and table tennis remains a sport hard to sell. Adham
Sherara, newly-elected President of the International Table Tennis
Federation, will find his road ahead is not smooth.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old Sherara, who took over Chinese Xu Yinsheng to head
the world table tennis ruling body, said he would continue his work to
make the sport more spectacular. The 61-year-old Xu didn't seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
In the day-long ITTF General Assembly, Pierre Albertini,
President of the French Table Tennis Association, edged out his
friend Hans Giesecke of Germany to become the new ITTF Deputy
President, a position vacated by Sherara.
</P>
<P>
The 40mm ball proposal, which was predicted to have a major
influence on the future of table tennis, was overruled in the
voting. 84 of 124 ITTF members voted for the proposal with 30
against. 10 abstained.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal was defeated by only two votes," said Sherara. "It
was close."
</P>
<P>
Sherara, who introduced a "3-P Policy" of popularization,
participation and profit to table tennis, favors the proposal to
enlarge the ball size from usual 38mm to 40mm in order to reduce speed
and spin and make the sport more attractive.
</P>
<P>
Sherara said he was more confident today than yesterday on the
40mm ball proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I expected the proposal to be overruled this time and I thought
the voting could 50-50 because some people are not sure what the
change of ball size will bring about," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now I am more confident because it is just two votes away from
reality. I will try to convince those who are not sure," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president said the proposal would be discussed during the
world team table tennis championships to be held in Malaysia in
February next year. "Hopefully it will pass," said Sherara.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to change the service rules suffered the same defeat
as the 40mm ball on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The most talked about and controversial aspect of table tennis
since the game was first played have been the rules relating to
service. Over the years there have been a host of ways developed by
players and coaches in an effort to gain the maximum advantage from
the service.
</P>
<P>
The proposal called for all players to serve in front of the
body, not level with the body and definitely not behind.
</P>
<P>
"The service rule change and the other proposal to make the ball
more visible by adding black and white lines to ball were defeated
easily," said Sherara, a language genius who speaks eight languages
including French, Italian, Spanish and Arabic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
