<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader to Visit Egypt Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi will
fly to Egypt on Wednesday for talks with President Hosni Mubarak,
an Egyptian official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This will be Gaddafi's first trip to Egypt since the United
Nations suspended air embargo on Libya in April, the official at
the Foreign Ministry said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The official said Gaddafi will meet with Mubarak for the
day-long talks in the Mediterranean town of Marsa Matrouh, 500
kilometers northwest of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The talks will focus on bilateral issues and Libya's efforts to
restore normal ties with other countries following its surrender
of two Libyans suspected of blowing up Pan Am Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, the official said. The explosion
killed 270 people, most of them American or British.
</P>
<P>
During an Egyptian visit in March, Gaddafi and Mubarak agreed
to set up joint ventures in the fishery industry and land
reclamation projects.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to urge Libya to begin implementing the
projects, and also to boost trade exchange.
</P>
<P>
In April, the U.N. Security Council suspended the embargo on
Libya, which it imposed in 1992 in a bid to force the Northern
African country to surrender the suspects for trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
