<HEADLINE> Ocalan Orders Kurdish Rebels to Halt Attacks in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan Tuesday ordered his followers
to halt attacks on Turkish targets and withdraw from Turkish
territory to give way to the establishment of peace.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan's appeal was disclosed to the Turkish press by his
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan, who was sentenced to death by Turkey's Ankara Security
Court in June, told the "mountain units" of the PKK to stop all
"armed struggle" and "withdraw beyond the borders" as of September
1 so that peace could be established.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer Dogan Erbas read a statement by Ocalan which said
that "In Turkey the fighting and violent atmosphere have formed an
obstacle blocking the development of human rights and democracy."
</P>
<P>
"The violence which has occurred primarily because of the
Kurdish problem plays a basic role in this. In order to get out of
the blind alley and find a solution to the problems, an end has to
be put to the violence," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason I am calling on the PKK to put an end to their
armed struggle as of September 1, 1999," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the PKK to withdraw their forces beyond the
boundaries in the interest of peace," it added.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by the Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and was brought to the Imrali prison on the Marmara
Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Its fighting
against Turkish government and civilian targets continues after
Ocalan was given the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts between the Turkish security forces and the PKK
militants have claimed over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
