<HEADLINE> Canada's New Cabinet Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- With a mid-term cabinet reshuffle
completed Tuesday, the newly announced Canadian cabinet was sworn
in at around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The "medium-sized" reshuffle brings at least four new faces to
the cabinet of "continuity and fresh ideas," according to the
Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of former Ontario Health Minister Elinor Caplan
is described by insiders as the most significant addition to the
cabinet. Ms. Caplan replaces Lucienne Robillard as minister of
citizenship and immigration.
</P>
<P>
Bob Nault of Northern Ontario and George Baker of Newfoundland
take over portfolios respectively from Indian Affairs Minister
Jane Stewart and Veterans Affairs Minister Fred Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
Toronto's Maria Minna is appointed minister for international
cooperation. David Anderson moves to the post of minister of
environment from his original duty as minister of fisheries.
Minister of National Revenue Herb Dhaliwal changes duty to become
new minister of fisheries.
</P>
<P>
Leaving the cabinet are Veterans Affairs Minister Fred Mifflin,
Environment Minister Christine Stewart, Treasury Board President
Marcel Masse, International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi and
Minister for International Cooperation Diane Marleau.
</P>
