<HEADLINE> EU To Give Full Room For GlobalOne Telecom Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
here Tuesday that GlobalOne, a European-American joint venture,
will be allowed to provide all telecommunications services in the
15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The EU antitrust authorities have cleared the joint venture
created in 1996 by Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom and Sprint
Corporation (US), but imposed a series of conditions reflecting
the lack of competition in the telecom sector then dominated by
national monoplies in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive arm, said a notice
about the intention has been published to invite "all interested
parties to comment before adopting a formal decision to this end."
</P>
<P>
The commission said its position is based on the market
developments since the creation of GlobalOne was approved in 1996,
and noted the other substantial competitors' entry into the
market, such as the joint venture between British Telecom (BT) and
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
"The home markets of GlobalOne's shareholders have been
completely liberalized and the market for global
telecommunications services now features a number of strong
competitors, especially the new BT-AT&AMP;T joint venture, which are
not subject to the same restrictions as GlobalOne," the EU
executive said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU antitrust authorities said the incoming decision will
enable GlobalOne "to be free to provide all telecommunications
services, including voice telephony, on both a resale and
facilities basis, in all the EU member states." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
