<HEADLINE> Uganda-Rwanda Ties Not Soured by Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Uganda and
Rwanda has not in the least been soured by the drastic differences
that emerged between the two rebel groups in the Congolese Rally
for Democracy (RDC), a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, state minister for regional cooperation, made
these remarks at a press briefing here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The difference is natural and expected. A mechanism has been
established to resolve this difference. Our relations have not
been damaged by it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is not supporting any of these two groups and Uganda is
not insisting that Wamba dia Wamba must sign the Lusaka cease-fire
agreement, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Uganda and Rwanda had been enjoying very good relations
and they are still doing what they can to bring to an end the
armed conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
When asked about Uganda's pullout from the central African
country, he said that his government would honor and respect the
agreement it signed in Lusaka on July 10 and would pull out all
its troops within 180 days after the true implementation of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
This year saw a split between what is known as RDC-Goma, backed
by Rwanda, and RDC-Kisangani, headed by Wamba and backed by
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
IIunga and his aides have rejected Wamba dia Wamba's leadership
and refused to recognize his legitimacy, which was the reason
given for a rebel failure to sign the accord in Lusaka that was
penned by President Laurent Kabila, his allies from Zimbabwe,
Angola and Namibia, and by Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
