<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Rwandan Ex-Ministers to Face Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) (C Three former ministers of
the Rwandan interim government have been transferred to the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) facing genocide
charges, the court said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three are Jerome Bicamumpaka, former Minister of Foreign
Affairs, Justin Mugenzi, former Minister of Commerce and Industry,
and Prosper Mugiraneza, former Minister for the Civil Service.
</P>
<P>
They were transferred to the ICTR detention facility in Arusha
in north Tanzania Saturday from Cameroon where they were arrested
and detained in April this year, the U.N. court said in a press
release reaching here.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily ethnic Tutsis and moderate
Hutus were massacred in the middle of 1994 in Rwanda. In November
that year, the United Nations Security Council set up the court
Arusha to try the chief architects of the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The three accused, together with Casimir Bizimungu, a former
Minister for Health who is already in custody in Arusha, are
jointly charged with genocide, conspiracy to commit genocide and
crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu was arrested in Kenya and transferred to the
tribunal's detention facility in Arusha in February this year.
</P>
<P>
However, as part of a strategy to seek joint trials calculated
to show the 1994 genocide as a far-reaching conspiracy in the
government at the time, the prosecutor is seeking a decision of
the trial chambers to allow a joint indictment of these four
individuals with several former senior government officials, five
of whom are already in custody in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The five are Edouard Karemera, former Minister of Interior,
Andre Rwamakuba, former Minister of Education, Mathieu
Ngirumpaste, former Director General of the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and President of National Revolutionary Development
Movement, as well as Joseph Nzirorera, former President of the
National Assembly and Secretary-General of the movement and
Juvenal Kajelijeli, former Bourgmestre of Mukingo.
</P>
<P>
The case is collectively referred as "the government case."
</P>
<P>
The total number of accused persons detained under the
authority of the tribunal is now 38, one of whom is in custody in
Texas, the United States, awaiting the result of an appeal
against his transfer to Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
