<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The price of cement stands at 200 Egyptian pounds
(58.82 U.S. dollars) per ton in Egypt, 50 pounds (14.71 dollars)
lower than the price last year due to excessive supply, the
country's Middle East News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to produce 22 million tons of cement this
year, up by 2 million tons from last year. In addition, the
private sector has imported 4 million tons of cement.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan on Monday decided to exempt a number of
imported electronic goods from custom duties and to lower custom
duties on other commodities in order to facilitate the supply of
certain goods at reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
The move was also aimed at encouraging various sectors to
update their equipment, and at preventing smuggling and illegal
entry of such equipment into the country.
</P>
<P>
Custom duties on computer sets and related supplies were
exempted and those on mobile telephones, video cameras, still
cameras, wrist watches and neckties were lowered to 5 percent
instead of 30 to 35 per cent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
said on Monday that Egypt will export to Portugal 30 million
U.S. dollars worth of cotton yarn, 5.88 million dollars of leather
products and 2.94 million dollars of ceramics.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili was quoted by Egypt's Middle East News Agency as saying
that Egypt will also export to Portugal 12,000 pieces of children
clothes and 10 containers of household appliances, including
washing machines, gas cookers and air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
He said Portugal's demand for Egyptian products is growing as a
result of exchanging visits by businessmen and efforts by the
Egyptian Trade Office to acquaint Portuguese consumers with
Egyptian goods.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will spend a total of some 1.194 billion
pounds (346 million U.S. dollars) in potable water and sanitary
drainage projects in Port Said governorate by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
The money will be spent on 68 projects, 48 of which are for
water treatment and 20 of which are for sanitary drainage.
</P>
<P>
And 50 percent of the capacity of these projects would serve
industrial zones, tourist villages and ships, said a report by the
Ministry of Housing and Urban Communities.
</P>
<P>
The projected Adiliya to Port Said water line would be
completed this year, with a total production capacity of 22,000
cubic meters per day at a cost of about 75 million pounds (21.7
million dollars), the Alam Al Yom newspaper quoted the report as
saying Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
