<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps Strengthen Police Security in Rwandan Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and donor partners are helping
strengthen police security in rural areas of Rwanda through a 5.5
million-U.S. dollar program, UNDP officials said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The program is providing training and housing accommodations
for local police. However, the lack of adequate living quarters of
Rwandan police officers in rural communities has been a major
obstacle to their recruitment in the past, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
In the northwestern communities of Karago and Stainsyi, police
are now on the job as the result of new housing constructed
through the effort.
</P>
<P>
"Security means peace, peace means development and development
means prosperity," said Stephen Browne, UNDP resident
representative in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"Having the communal police in place has clearly provided
security to the local community and has encouraged them to go
forward and to develop the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom and the
United States are among the donors that have provided funding to
the initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
