<HEADLINE> S. African Deputy President Urges to Revitalize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Jacob Zuma called on the nation Tuesday to undertake the
task of revitalizing education.
</P>
<P>
Revitalizing education, which had been damaged by years of
apartheid rule, should focus not only on "lost" values from the
past, but perhaps more importantly on "seeking new ways to meet
new times", Zuma told a South African Council of Churches
workshop on education held here.
</P>
<P>
It was imperative that schools become centers of community and
cultural life, and that parents be encouraged to play a role as
important stakeholders in education, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
This revitalization required not simply recovery or
resuscitation, but a renewal, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was time for South Africans to pick up the pieces of their
damaged minds and souls and undertake the task of reconstructing
themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
There was a serious moral vacuum in society, he said,
stressing that " the loss of respect for human life and dignity
has reached endemic proportions today".
</P>
<P>
"If humanity is central to our thoughts and actions, if to be
fully human and true to ourselves are our starting points, then we
cannot go wrong in creating a better life for all our people," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Apartheid, he said, had literally "messed up" people's morality
and distorted the values of society, changing people's outlooks in
such a way that many could no longer see themselves as human.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said the Church, which had been active in shaping society
for so long in all spheres of life, should not now abandon its
task.
</P>
<P>
It was "the most qualified" to make society conscious of the
value system that should be underpinning the transformation
agenda, and particularly transformation of the education system.
</P>
</TEXT>
