<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Grows Rapidly in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Promoted by an average of 5-6
percent of economic growth in the past three years, construction
has become one of the fastest growing sectors in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of the Middle East Economic
Digest (MEED), construction will be further boosted in Egypt as
the government presses ahead with new infrastructure schemes and
private sector development projects mushroom.
</P>
<P>
The recent government figures showed that construction,
excluding the industry, electricity and oil and gas sectors,
accounted for 14.1 billion Egyptian pounds (4.15 billion U.S.
dollars) out of the gross domestic product of 253.1 billion pounds
(74.44 billion dollars) in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending on June
30.
</P>
<P>
The London-based MEED, which focuses on Mideast economy and
business, attributed much of the impetus for the expansion of the
construction sector to the government's promotion of new
development zones, the main of which are in the Suez Gulf and East
Port Said.
</P>
<P>
In the Suez development zone, work is proceeding rapidly on the
new port of Sokhna, which will serve the zone.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-registered Archirodon Construction (Overseas) is
building the quay walls for 60 million dollars, and the
European/U.S. Great Lake Group is carrying out the 105 million
dollars dredging contract.
</P>
<P>
Bids from six international groups are also under evaluation
for the contract to build and operate a water supply system for
the development zone.
</P>
<P>
Work is getting under way on the new East Port Said container
terminal. An international consortium led by Jan de Nul of Belgium
is carrying out the 211 million dollars dredging and breakwater
construction contract, and a 60 million dollars contract has just
been awarded to a joint venture of the local Arabian International
construction and Italy's Rodio for the quay walls job.
</P>
<P>
Ten prequalified international groups are also preparing to bid
for a contract to design, build and operate a road tunnel under
the Suez Canal to provide access to the East Port Said terminal
and the adjacent industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
The government is also looking to the private sector to invest
in new airport projects. Contracts have already been awarded for
airports that will serve new tourism destinations: Mersa Alam on
the Red Sea, El-Alamein on the Mediterranean and Ras El-Sidr on
the Gulf of Suez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
