<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Recommends Probing Sale of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Parliament Tuesday
afternoon recommended a thorough investigation into the closure
and sale of the Cooperative Bank.
</P>
<P>
This motion was tabled at the afternoon session and supported
by Prime Minister Appolo Nsibambi and some other members of
parliament, Radio Uganda reported Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The backers of the motion said that a special committee should
be instituted in order to investigate this matter. The closure
and alleged sale of the bank had exerted negative impact on the
society both politically and economically, they said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the government is transparent and
would stand the test of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Uganda, central bank of the east African country,
closed the bank in May this year, convinced that the bank was
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Gerald Ssendaula said that the closure of the
bank was timely because the bank directors had been robbing the
depositors' money.
</P>
<P>
The Cooperative Bank had some 110,000 depositors across the
country when it was closed.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan MPs are complaining about the slow development of the
country's economy. Some of them believe that the 7.8 percent
growth rate of gross domestic product (GDP) as reported in the new
fiscal budget was exaggerated because there is little improvement
in common people's life. 
</P>
