<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Bigger U.N. Presence in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has recommended increasing a U.N. mission in Sierra
Leone to 210 observers from 70 to help implement a recently signed
peace accord between the government and rebels, a U.N. official
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his written report to the U.N. Security Council late Monday,
Annan said a larger U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra Leone
(UNOMSIL) would be needed, depending on a division of labor to be
worked out between the United Nations and a large Nigerian-led
West African force, known as the ECOMOG, that has been supporting
the Sierra Leonean government.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Agreement, signed on July 7 in Togo's capital of
Lome, requires the UNMSIL to perform significantly expanded as
well as new tasks in close coordination with the ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the major disarmament and demobilization effort,
implementation of the Lome agreement would require substantial
numbers of peacekeepers throughout the country and the deployment
of additional U.N. military observers, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The number of UNOMSIL military observers would increase to
210," he said, adding that the proposed U.N. mission would be well
above the current strength of about 50 and the authorized strength
of 70.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG's mandate would need to be revised by the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in consultation with the
United Nations, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Once there was an understanding on the task, strengths and
mandates of the ECOMOG and the U.N. special representative for
Sierra Leone, Francis Okelo of Uganda, Annan said he would submit
a more comprehensive report to the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
