<HEADLINE> African Stowaway Youths Have Letter on Them </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The two African youths, who were
found dead in an airplane landing gear compartment at the Belgian
national airport, had a letter on them appealing for a better life
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The letter, found prior to Tuesday's autopsy by Belgian justice
authorities to decide the cause of their deaths, appealed to the
European leaders to pay attention to the youths in Africa that has
been plagued by civil wars.
</P>
<P>
The two youths, identified as Koita Yaguine, 15, and Tounkara
Fode, 16, said in the letter that they took the risk to try to
come to Europe for a better opportunity of education, recreation
and sports.
</P>
<P>
The two youths, from Guinea, were found dead Monday in an
under-the-wing landing gear compartment of a Sabena Airbus
A330-300.
</P>
<P>
A strange odor led airport re-fueling technicians to the
discovery of the bodies from the compartment.
</P>
<P>
The airport medical personnel said that the deaths could be
caused by the low temperature high up in the sky during the
flight.
</P>
<P>
The Sabena airliner initiated its flight from Conakry of Guinea
with a stopover at Bamako of Mali before arriving in the Belgian
capital.
</P>
<P>
No one knows for sure where the two stowaways got into the
compartment though it is supposed to be routinely checked at each
airport before taking off.
</P>
<P>
At the cruise height of 10,000 meters, the ambient temperature
around the airplane can be 50 degrees or 55 degrees Celsius below
zero. Though it may be a bit warmer inside the landing gear
compartment, the lack of oxygen at that altitude is another deadly
factor during flight.
</P>
<P>
The chance is rare for anyone to survive such a stowaway voyage
though a Senegalese youth managed to survive a five-hour stowaway
flight from Dakar to Lyon of France on January 26 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
