<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese civilian was wounded
Tuesday in Israeli shelling on south Lebanon villages, Lebanon's
state-run National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mariam Srour, 60, was injured by shrapnels of Israeli shells
landed on her village of Mansouri just outside the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
She was transferred to a nearby hospital in Tyre, the country's
southern coastal city. Doctors said she was in a stable condition.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Israeli warplanes also blasted villages in
the Iqlim Toufah region on the edge of the occupied border zone
with air-to-surface missiles.
</P>
<P>
There have been no reports about casualties from the air raids
which have been confirmed by Israeli army, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this year, a total of 17 Lebanese civilians
have been killed and more than 100 wounded in conflicts between
Israeli forces and Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli forces out of the country. 
