<HEADLINE> Five Key Industries to Be Boosted in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 3 (Xinhua) - Five key industries in Thailand
are expected to be boosted as the country's Board of Investment
(BOI) has planned to set up a new panel to help regenerate the
economy, the Thai News Agency (TNA) quoted BOI Secretary-General
Sataporn Kavitanonda as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The five industries are steel and construction materials,
petrochemicals and petroleum products, textile, paper and pulp,
and ceramics.
</P>
<P>
Sataporn said that the panel, consisting of representatives
from the ministries of commerce, industry and finance and the Bank
of Thailand, will help enhance the industries' competitiveness in
overseas markets by granting them trade privileges, including tax
incentives, and helping restructure their corporate and debt
structures.
</P>
<P>
Sataporn said that if the five key industries were virtually
pushed through difficulties, they would help spur other economic
activities and eventually revive Thailand's overall economic
system.
</P>
<P>
The five industries, which had recorded high growth rates and
business prospects, with value of approved investment reaching 630
billion baht (17 billion U.S. dollars) two years ago, were among
the hardest hit during the economic crisis, which brought the Thai
economy to an eight percent recession last year.
</P>
<P>
Though having been in red since the economic crisis in
mid-1997, the five industries still have high business potential,
Sataporn said.
</P>
<P>
BOI's move coincided with its announcement that it had achieved
in helping boost exports of 660 business firms under its promotion
and support schemes, which were led by electronic and electrical
appliance industries and automobiles, TNA said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the firms on average increased by eight percent in
the first half of this year compared with the same period last
year, with overall value amounting to 12.7 billion dollars, or 48
percent of the country's total exports during the first half of
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
