<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Clothing Exports to S. Africa Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Clothing Council and
the Zimbabwe Clothing Manufacturers Association Tuesday announced
the new quota system for clothing exports to South Africa, showing
a remarkable increase.
</P>
<P>
The two associations announced in a statement that the quota
for t- shirts, singlets, knitted or crocheted vests would increase
from 400,000 to one million, while that of men's or boy's
trousers, bib and brace overalls, breeches and shorts would
increase from 320,000 to one million.
</P>
<P>
The new quota for all other tariff clothing headings would be
1,127,000.
</P>
<P>
The new quota system comes in the wake of discussions held
between South African Trade Minister Alec Erwin and Zimbabwean
Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira and other trade
and industry representatives from both countries at the recent
Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Congress held in Bulawayo,
Zimbabwe's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
While the new quotas had been a welcome development in the
clothing industry, they still fell short of what the industry had
been pushing for during previous trade discussions.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe was seeking a free trade area to correct the imbalance
of trade between the two countries which is in favor of South
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
