<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Intensify Efforts to Reconcile Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government will
intensify its efforts aimed at ironing out the differences between
the main factions of the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RDC) in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Regional Cooperation Amama Mbabazi made this
pledge during a press conference here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from the faction of RDC headed by Emile IIunga met
 President Yoweri Museveni Monday and they discussed issues
regarding the reconciliation among the rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
"This will help bring to an end the fighting in the DRC and it
is in the interest of Congo and the region," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"It's true that within RDC differences emerged. Uganda's
position is neutral first and foremost. We sincerely hope the
differences would be resolved properly," he added.
</P>
<P>
The RDC was split into two factions this year reportedly
supported respectively by Uganda and Rwanda. Their differences in
both strategies and tactics to be used against the DRC government
forces and allied forces have remained sticking point in their
reconciliation efforts.
</P>
<P>
They held reconciliation talks at Kabale District in western
Uganda after the signing of Lusaka cease-fire agreement on July
10.
</P>
<P>
There has been dispute as to who should sign the agreement on
behalf of all the rebel forces. Both Kisangani-based Wamba dia
Wambia and Goma-based Emile IIunga wanted to sign it. Their
dispute and failure to sign the agreement led to the postponement
of its implementation.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the head of the other rebel group Jean Pierre Bemba,
whose Congolese Liberation Movement has been fighting notably in
the northwest of the vast central African country, signed the
cease-fire agreement in the Zambian capital of Lusaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
