<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Still Hopes to Quit COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania still wishes to
quit the Common Market for East and Southern Africa (COMESA) after
holding talks with a delegation from the regional organization
that left here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of COMESA Council of Ministers, Nicholas Biwott, said
here Tuesday that he and other leaders of the implementation
committee of the regional organization have visited Tanzania to
persuade the country not to quit its membership.
</P>
<P>
Biwott said he is optimistic that Tanzania will rethink its
decision of pulling out of the 21-member organization. "We are
confident that closer discussions will enable us to resolve the
matter," he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, Tanzanian Minister of Industries and Commerce, Iddi
Simba, told a press conference in Dar es Salaam in the same day
that Tanzania will stick to its position of pulling out of the
COMESA for economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
Simba said his country reached the decision of pulling out of
the COMESA after doing a research on how much Tanzania can benefit
from the regional economic bloc.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is better for Tanzania to stick to smaller
blocs such as the 14-member Southern African Development Community
(SADC), and the East African Cooperation that comprises Kenya,
Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA was set up in 1994 with a vision to reach a zero
taxation rate for intra-region imports next year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's manufacturers have expressed concern that zero
tariffs would damage its local industries with the flooding of
imported goods from other COMESA members.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Tanzania would like to trade with SADC and
EAC members rather than COMESA countries.
</P>
<P>
On July 21, the minister suddenly announced at the National
Assembly that Tanzania plans to quit the COMESA. His announcement
surprised the organization a lot as Tanzania has always been an
active member.
</P>
<P>
With an annual import bill of around 32 billion U.S. dollars,
the COMESA forms a major market place for both internal and
external trading.
</P>
<P>
The member countries are Angola, Burundi, the Comoros, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea,
Ethiopia, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Namibia, Rwanda,
Seychelles, Sudan, Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
