<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate to Investigate its President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's 109-member upper house of
 legislature voted Tuesday to allow three of its committees to
investigate allegations of its president Even Enwerem.
</P>
<P>
The latest edition of "Tell", a Lagos-based weekly magazine,
alleged that the senate president was convicted for stealing in
1945 while serving as a revenue clerk under the British colonial
government and variously falsified his age for public office.
</P>
<P>
The Committee on Judiciary and Ethics, Security and
Intelligence as well as Code of Conduct and Public Petitions were
ordered to investigate the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Enwerem has consistently denied the allegations and on Saturday
 described it as part of a campaign to "bring me down and ridicule
the office."
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the committees, expected to complete their
work within seven days, coincided with the conviction of former
speaker of the lower house for perjury and forgery.
</P>
<P>
"Chief Enwerem is no longer a private and ordinary citizen and
any allegation impinging on this person is of utmost concern to
the senate and the entire nation," said Senator Idris Abubakar who
moved the motion for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
He said the Senate should not be seen to be sweeping the issue
under the carpet after the events of the past few weeks, a
reference to the resignation of the speaker of the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Senate Committee on Information, Senator
Ibrahim Mantu said the decision to investigate the president,
third in the country's political hierarchy, was reached after a
meeting of the "political party cause". 
</P>
</TEXT>
