<HEADLINE> Resigned Nigerian Speaker Gets Symbolic Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Alhaji Buhari, resigned speaker of
Nigeria's lower house of parliament, was fined 2,000 naira (19
U.S. dollars) Tuesday after pleading guilty to forgery and
perjury.
</P>
<P>
An Abuja magistrate court made the decision, which surprised
hundreds of Buhari's countrymen who thronged the court to hear the
judgment in the landmark case.
</P>
<P>
The magistrate later admitted he was influenced by last week's
"admission of guilt" by the former speaker.
</P>
<P>
"I was moved by the confession and compelled to temper justice
with mercy," the magistrate said, adding that his leniency was
justified by the former speaker's remorse.
</P>
<P>
The disgraced speaker resigned from the leadership of the House
of Representatives two weeks ago in a scandal that threw Nigeria's
democracy into turmoil only weeks after the end of long military
rule.
</P>
<P>
Buhari admitted that he was only 29, not 36 as he had claimed,
and was therefore too young to serve in parliament. He also
admitted that his claim to have an academic degree from the
University of Toronto was false.
</P>
<P>
The 360-member House of Representatives had voted the day when
the speaker resigned to forgive Buhari but President Olusegun
Obasanjo's government decided to prosecute him anyway.
</P>
<P>
The speaker of the house ranks the fourth in Nigeria's
constitutional hierarchy. The convening of an elected National
Assembly on June 3 ended more than 15 years in which Nigeria's law
were made by military decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
