<HEADLINE> Capital Outflows from Kenya Slows Down in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The exodus of foreign capitals
from Kenya slowed in July as the market reacted to a new
government reform plan that put conservationist Richard Leakey to
head the civil service.
</P>
<P>
Figures issued by Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) Tuesday showed
that net capital outflows by foreign investors dropped to 531,407
U.S. dollars in July from 1.34 million dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners brought 67,090 dollars into the market but took out
598,497 dollars compared with inflows of 47,992 dollars and
outflows of 1.39 million dollars in June, according to NSE data.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said President Daniel arap Moi's announcement on July
23 that he would fully support Leakey in a campaign to rid
government of corruption and inefficiency had eased investors'
nerves.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) suspended a
205-million-dollar loan package to Kenya in 1997 in protest
against poor governance and corruption in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts say that the Leakey team could get the loan
talks back on track in the coming months if it starts implementing
anti-graft measures.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan shilling remained steady through July, trading in
the 72 to 74.50 range against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
