<HEADLINE> Urgent: Canada's New Cabinet Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- With a mid-term cabinet shuffle
completed Tuesday, the newly announced Canadian cabinet was sworn in
at around 2 p.m..
</P>
<P>
The "medium-sized" shuffle brings five new faces to the cabinet of
"continuity and fresh ideas," according to the Prime Minister's
Office.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of former Ontario Health Minister Elinor Caplan is
described by insiders as the most significant addition to the cabinet.
Ms. Caplan replaces Lucienne Robillard as Minister of Citizenship and
Immigration.
</P>
<P>
Bob Nault of Northern Ontario and George Baker of Newfoundland take
over portfolios respectively from Indian Affairs Minister Jane Stewart
and Veterans Affairs Minister Fred Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
Toronto's Maria Minna is appointed Minister for International
Cooperation, while Martin Cauchon assumes duty as Minister of National
Revenue.
</P>
<P>
David Anderson moves to the post of Minister of
Environment from his original duty as Minister of Fisheries. Minister
of National Revenue Herb Dhaliwal changes duty to become new Minister
of Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
Leaving the cabinet are Veterans Affairs Minister Fred Mifflin,
Environment Minister Christine Stewart, Treasury Board President
Marcel Masse, international Trade Minister Sergio Marchi and Minister
for International cooperation Diane Marleau.
</P>
<P>
Many of the cabinet's most prominent ministers stay at their posts,
including Minister of Finance Paul Martin, Minister of Health Allan
Rock, Minister of Foreign Affairs Lloyd Axworthy, Minister of
Transport David Collenette, Minister of Justice Anne Mclellan and
Minister of Industry John Manley.
</P>
<P>
The shuffle is reported by the local media to be a signal that
Prime Minister Jean Chretien has no plans to retire any time soon.
Rather, he is intent on revitalizing his government with a bold new
team and a more inspirational vision to lead the country into the new
millenium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
