<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq Moving Anti-Aircraft Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon alleged on
Tuesday that Iraq had moved more anti-aircraft missiles into the
southern no-fly zone, possibly to enforce its challenge to U.S.
and British invading warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon described the move as fitting "a
pattern of Iraqi behavior.
</P>
<P>
"It's episodic," he said. "There's an ebb and flow to this
... Sometimes they're more aggressive at trying to -- or
appearing to try to -- ambush our planes, or preparing to do
that, than they are at other times."
</P>
<P>
Bacon said it might send a signal that Iraq was "not taking
the no-fly zone seriously."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has denounced the no-fly zones in both its northern and
southern parts, imposed by the United States and Britain since
the 1991 Gulf War, as violation of its sovereignty and said it
would challenge any Western warplanes invading its air space.
</P>
<P>
The United States has exchanged fires with Iraq nearly 110
times this year when Iraq's anti-aircraft system fired at U.S. and
British planes patrolling the two no-fly zones. 
</P>
