<HEADLINE> United Nations Gains Momentum in Disarmament Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- About 40 percent of the
worldwide flow of small arms comes from illicit trafficking,
serving warlords, drug traffickers, terrorists and other
criminals, a U.N. spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, told a press conference here
that five hundred million light weapons are currently in
circulation around the world.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately, we have several initiatives in response to this
problem to report," he said.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from all African countries as well as
non-governmental organizations and research institutions are in
the middle of a three-day U.N.-organized meeting in Lome, capital
of Togo, on illicit trafficking in small arms in Africa. The
meeting, which will end Wednesday, is aimed at broadening
understanding of the problem, propose policies in response, and
define the role of the United Nations in the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a three-day U.N.-organized regional disarmament
meeting on security concepts in the changing world is starting
Tuesday in Ulan Bator, capital of Mongolia. Participants will deal
with such issues as nuclear-free-zones, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
