<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Monday's
train collision rose to 278 on Wednesday, General Manager of N. F.
Railway Rajendra Nath said in Gaisal, West Bengal.
</P>
<P>
"This is more or less the final figure. All the bogies have
been cut open and we do not expect to find very many bodies from
the debris any more," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said cranes were being used to access the interiors of the
badly damaged bogies and the debris would be cleared by Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The bodies have been kept at the North Bengal Medical College
and Islampur Hospitals for identification.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief Commissioner of Railway Safety M. Mani said he
did not think sabotage was the cause of the train disaster, adding
that the exact cause of the tragedy would be established only
after the inquiry which will start Thursday and end on August 8.
</P>
