<HEADLINE> Islamabad Asked to Ensure Security of Americans in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABADD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States has asked
Islamabad to guarantee the security of Americans in Pakistan who
are worrying about possible attacks from some Islamic groups,
informed sources here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Several militant Islamic groups have threatened to target
Americans in Pakistan if the United States strikes bases in
neighboring Afghanistan that Washington believes to be used by
Osama bin Laden, the Saudi dissident wanted by it.
</P>
<P>
The United States has accused Osama of masterminding the
bombings of U.S. embassies in East Africa last August.
</P>
<P>
Saturday is the first anniversary of those bombings, which left
more than 200 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The United States fired cruise missiles at the alleged training
camps of Osama in Afghanistan on August 20 last year but, Osama
was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
Osama has denied his involvement in the U.S. embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
Jamiat-e-Islami, the biggist religious party in Pakistan,
recently held several large-scale rallies in which party leaders
called for attacks against Americans if Washington carries out new
strikes against Osama, who is regarded as a hero by many Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Pakistani government ruled out the
possibility of letting the United States use its territory to
launch attacks on Osama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
