<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stWritethru: 9 Bodies Found in Philippine Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers Wednesday recovered nine
bodies of people who died in a huge cave-in following a landslide
Tuesday night in a housing subdivision in the northern
Philippines, the National Disaster Coordinating Center (NDCC)
said.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC also feared that 50 people might have been killed in
the tragic disaster which struck the six-hectare Cherry Hill
subdivision in Antipolo City in Rizal province.
</P>
<P>
The subdivision had about 400 concrete houses, more than 300 of
them have been occupied, said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
According to the NDCC, more than 200 soldiers are working
round-the-clock to find survivors in the worst disaster to hit the
country this year, spawned by rampaging floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Four days of continuous rains flooded northern and central
Luzon island, including Metro Manila, killing at least 48 people
and injuring 32 others with many more missing.
</P>
<P>
The official list of missing persons was placed at 12 but this
did not include the people who were believed inside the 75 to 80
houses that were buried when an avalanche of boulders and mud
rolled over the subdivision.
</P>
<P>
Crumbled houses, twisted steel, giant boulders and mud have
made rescue efforts difficult, said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
Besides the nine dead, there were 30 injured who were brought
to the hospitals by military rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are worried that the number of fatalities could
rise when rescue workers finish sorting out of the debris from the
devastated Antipolo housing area.
</P>
<P>
The search, rescue and retrieval operations were hampered by
heavy rains, but retrieval operations will continue until the
six-hectare subdivision has been cleared, the NDCC said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, various government agencies have said action would
be taken against people and agencies responsible for the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said Wednesday that he will
on Thursday summon government officials tasked to monitor housing
projects and environment, and the local officials and ask them to
explain what caused the Antipolo landslides.
</P>
<P>
Observers blamed the conversion of the forest lands in Antipolo
into residential centers as part of the cause of the landslide.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said landslides have been occurring in many areas of
the country and now is the time to strictly enforce a ban on
illegal quarrying and illegal logging.
</P>
<P>
"We really need reforestation and tree planting to prevent
floods," said the president, adding that the only way the country
could put an end to landslides is to put an end to the denudation
of forests.
</P>
<P>
The southwest monsoon rain was spawned by what authorities
claimed as part of the La Nina phenomenon which the country has
been expecting since October last year.
</P>
<P>
At least 17,180 families or 82,591 people were displaced and
64.623 million pesos (1.6 million U.S. dollars) worth of crops and
infrastructure destroyed in the last four days of incessant rains.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has declared a state of calamity in Metro Manila and
three nearby provinces of Rizal, Pangasinan and Pampanga on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies have distributed ready-to-eat food, rice,
drinking water and blankets to flood victims who are temporarily
housed in public schools.
</P>
<P>
Authorities had to gradually release waters from three dam
sites -- Binga and Ambuklao in Benguet province and Angat in
Bulacan province.
</P>
<P>
Metro Manila and practically many parts of northern and central
Luzon island have been submerged following unabated rainfall the
past four days.
</P>
<P>
Edmundo Larroza, Officer-in-Charge of the Philippine National
Police, warned Wednesday hoarders, profiteers and other
unscrupulous traders to refrain from taking advantage of the
ongoing calamity situation.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some unscrupulous traders in these areas
have hiked prices of basic commodities by as much as 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological authorities predicted that monsoon rains
will still prevail over the western sections of Luzon island in
the next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Return Bodies of Guinean Stowaway Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Belgium is to return the bodies
of the two Guinean youths who were found dead in an airplane
landing gear compartment, a local official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of Koita Yaguine and Tounkara Fode will be
transported back to their country of Guinea and the Belgian
government will cover the cost for the transport, according to the
spokesperson of the Brussels municipal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
But the official did not say when the bodies would be returned.
</P>
<P>
The two Guinean youths, aged 15 and 16 respectively, were found
dead Monday in the right under-the-wing compartment for storing
landing gears of an Airbus A330-300. The airplane belongs to the
Belgian carrier Sabena.
</P>
<P>
A letter was found on them before Tuesday's autopsy that
confirmed that low temperature during flight caused their death.
</P>
<P>
The two youths appealed in their letter to the European leaders
to pay attention to the youths in Africa that has been plagued by
civil wars.
</P>
<P>
They said in the letter that they took the risk to try to come
to Europe the way they chose for a better opportunity of
education, recreation and sports.
</P>
<P>
The Sabena airliner initiated its flight from Conakry of Guinea
with a stopover at Bamako of Mali before arriving in the Belgian
capital Monday.
</P>
<P>
No one knows for sure when the two stowaways got into the
compartment though it is supposed to be routinely checked at each
airport before taking off.
</P>
<P>
At the cruise height of 10,000 meters, the ambient temperature
around the airplane can be 50 degrees or 55 degrees Celsius below
zero. Though it may be a bit warmer inside the landing gear
compartment, the lack of oxygen at that altitude is another deadly
factor during flight.
</P>
<P>
The chance is rare for anyone to survive such a stowaway voyage
though a Senegalese youth managed to survive a five-hour stowaway
flight from Dakar to Lyon of France on January 26 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andorra Takes Steps To Prevent Cigarette Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Andorran authorities are
enforcing a number of legal and administrative measures aimed to
prevent cigarette smuggling, the European Commission said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The legal steps included the law on frauds in customs matters
and the law on the control of sensitive goods, as well as the law
modifying the Penal Code by introducing smuggling as an offense.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) executive arm said it had close
consultations with Andorra before Europe's principality took the
legal steps. Andorra's adoption of the new legislation is regarded
as the final step in a series of developments which started during
1996, when the small country was identified as one of the main
sources of smuggled cigarettes in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The commission said large quantities of cigarettes were
produced, or imported and stored in Adorra for smuggling into the
other places. Therefore, both EU member states and the EU as a
whole lost about 400 million euros (some 428 million U.S. dollars)
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
During 1998, illegal cigarette activity was remarkably reduced
after the Andorran authorities showed a positive attitude, coupled
with high levels of cooperation and actions taken by the
neighboring member states, the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"To this extent, Andorra is no longer considered to be a major
source of smuggled cigarettes affecting the EU," it added.
</P>
<P>
The cigarette smuggling was organized on a large scale by
international criminal organizations. Recipients of the smuggled
cigarette consignments have included Andorra's near neighboring
countries such as Spain and France, but large-scale shipments were
also destined for the British and Irishi black markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Rise 0.7 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
reported Wednesday that orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods increased 0.7 percent in June, led by higher demand for
autos and electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
The department said June's gain followed a 1 percent increase
in May, a little less than what the government previously
estimated. But it marked the 10th increase in the last 13 months.
</P>
<P>
It is the transportation sector which helped bolster June's
overall performance with a 2.3 percent increase, the report said.
A rise in orders for autos and car parts more than offset a
decrease in orders for airplane and aircraft parts. Transportation
posted a hefty 9.9 percent gain in May.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile transportation category, factory
orders would have risen only 0.5 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Orders for electronic and other electrical equipment, the
category that includes household appliances and communications
equipment, jumped 2.4 percent in June, following a drop of 0.9
percent in May.
</P>
<P>
June's overall gain in factory orders came despite a steep 5.1
percent decrease in orders for industrial machinery and equipment,
the sector that includes computers. It was the second straight
monthly decline. In May, orders for industrial machinery fell 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The department's report also offered some positive signs for
the steel industry. Orders for primary metals, the category that
includes steel, rose 0.4 percent in June, following gains in April
and May. The steel industry has been one of the hardest hit by the
world financial crisis, suffering from a flood of cheaper imported
steel.
</P>
<P>
In june, orders for durable goods rose 0.4 percent while orders
for nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, increased 1.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the solid showing in overall factory orders in
June appears to be good news for the U.S. manufacturing sector,
which has been hard-hit and is now recovering from the global
economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
