<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Town Changes Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Somali major faction leader
Hussein Mohamed Aidid recaptured the town of Aw-Dhegleh, some 80
Kilometers south of the capital, from its rival Digil Salvation
Army (DSA) which occupied the farming town for only about one day.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources, militiamen loyal to faction
leader Aidid recaptured the town with battle wagons and about a
hundred heavily armed soldiers and chased the DSA forces out of
the town Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
DSA spokesman, Asad Abdi Mohamed, who told reporters here in
Mogadishu Wednesday, has confirmed the fall of the farming town,
saying its only "a tactful retreat to the bush."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the town is now "no man's land".
</P>
<P>
While Hussein Hassan Diriyeh, who claimed himself as the head
of the town's security, said that town is calm Wednesday and under
full control of the Aidid's forces.
</P>
<P>
Diriyeh added that the DSA fighters have also attacked the
neighboring village of Barirreh, about eight kilometers east of
Aw-Dhegleh town, and was met with the defense of his forces.
</P>
<P>
There are no exact casualty figures available at this stage.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources confirmed that at least eight civilians,
including six women were killed and a dozen of others were wounded
in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The warring sides exchanged verbal attacks after the fighting.
The forces of Aidid accused the DSA as bandits for killing
civilians, raping and looting in the town.
</P>
<P>
While, the DSA forces also accused Aidid's forces for the same
crimes. The DSA spokesman said Aidid's men have made a nuisance
in the region by killing a businessman in Badleh village after
looting 2.5 million Somali Shillings worth of about 220 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources said that both sides have looted the town
and the nearby villages of Barirreh and Badleh.
</P>
<P>
The DSA spokesman has warned both local and international aid
agencies not to use the Km-50 airstrip, which is among their first
targets of attack, and that if the warning is defied, the
spokesman said, his faction won't shoulder responsibility of any
damage or losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
