<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Power Shortage to Be Relieved Soon: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will have enough power
early next year when two new generators out of the five under the
Owen Falls Dam Extension project start operation.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Uganda Electricity Board Generation
Manager Alex Mugoya during a tour of the project with the State
Minister for Energy and Mineral Development Francis Babu, Radio
Uganda reported Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The extra 80 megawatts of electricity generated by the two
generators are an addition to the 180 megawatts being currently
produced by the existing Owen Falls dam project built in 1954
which was upgraded from the original 150 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The minster said that the power shortage in Uganda is not only
due to insufficient capacity but there was need to improve
efficiency in transmission and distribution.
</P>
<P>
Illegal consumption should be uprooted if the demand is to be
met and load shedding to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
This is going to be addressed in the new electricity bill to be
tabled in Parliament soon, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Power shortage hinders Uganda's industrial development and
scares away some potential investors. The country is currently
producing 180 megawatts each year, some 80 megawatts short of
demand. The government is to extend the Owen Falls project and to
set up some more power plants in the lower reaches of the Nile
River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
