<HEADLINE> Taliban Chief Urges Opposition to Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Declaring general amnesty, the
supreme leader of Afghanistan's ruling Taliban militia, Mulla
Muhammad Omar, Wednesday urged the opposition to surrender.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued from the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar, Omar appealed to those still in the ranks of the
anti-Taliban northern alliance to lay down arms and abandon
opposition to the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Omar said his militia were now very close to the final victory
in achieving the objectives of maintaining peace and security in
the whole Afghanistan, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In a latest major offensive launched last week, the Taliban
captured a few strategic towns, forcing the troops loyal to
opposition commander Ahmad Shah Masood to retreat into the
Panjsher valley.
</P>
<P>
Announcing general amnesty, Omar said it was their "Islamic
obligation" to treat the opponents in accordance with Islamic
injunctions and tenets.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, he said, do not believe in personal revenge and
their operations were aimed at restoring peace and order and
enforcing a true Islamic system in the country.
</P>
<P>
Omar urged the Afghans to realize that they are being "used" by
those opposition leaders for their "vested interests and nefarious
designs."
</P>
<P>
He assured protection of life and property to those who
surrender to the "Islamic Emirate" which the Taliban have
established in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
If they continue to oppose the emirate, the Taliban leader
warned, it will be considered "a revolt." 
</P>
</TEXT>
