<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Government Sells Four Lots of Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Lands Department
sold four government lots for a total of 788.5 million HK dollars
(101 million U.S. dollars) at a public auction Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The auction, the third this year, attracted the participation
of mainly small and medium-sized land developers. Big developers,
however, stay on the sideline as the four lots are relatively
small.
</P>
<P>
Among a limited supply of coveted land in Hong Kong, the plot
at the Peak on Hong Kong Island was regarded as the most
successful sale at the auction, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
The 2,463-square-meter site that was designated for luxury
residence was sold for 134 million HK dollars (17.7 million U.S.
dollars), well above the opening price of 88 million HK dollars (
11.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The result demonstrated the developers' confidence with the
market potential of luxury residential lots, according to Charles
Lai, a property strategy consultant.
</P>
<P>
He said developers are quite cautious of investing in the
ordinary residential lots, referring to the sales of the two plots
at Tuen Mun of the New Territories, which were sold for 330
million HK dollars (42.3 million U.S. dollars) and 320 million HK
dollars (41 million U.S. dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it is impossible to have too high land and housing
prices, because many local employees are faced with salary cut and
could not afford high housing expenditure, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lai said the sale of the lot at Cheung Chau of the New
Territories was a little lower than the market expectation and it
was sold only at the opening price of 4.5 million HK dollars (577,
000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said the government put the four lots on
the market in order to create and maintain a stable property
market.
</P>
<P>
The price indicates what the market wishes to pay, and the
market is now in a reasonable state, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
Land sale is traditionally a major source of government revenue
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended land sales at the end of June 1998 in
a bid to shore up sagging property prices hit by the Asian
financial crisis. Land auction resumed last April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lawmaker Condemns U.S. Congressional Bill (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lee's rhetoric was also opposed by the international community,
the Chinese official said, adding: "Lee, scolded by all, has
plunged himself into an isolated corner."
</P>
<P>
For the U.S. side, President Bill Clinton has time and again
reiterated the U.S. stance to stick to the "one China" policy and
expressed "three nots" in line with the three Sino-U.S. joint
communiques, namely, not supporting the independence of Taiwan,
not supporting "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan," and not
supporting Taiwan's entry into any international organization
composed of sovereign states, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Even under such circumstances, Brown and others still openly
asked the U.S. to abandon the "one China" policy, and support "one
China, one Taiwan" or the "independence of Taiwan" in a bid to
support Lee and other separatists who are playing with fire, he
said.
</P>
