<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House and Senate Republicans agreed Tuesday night on a
compromise plan to cut all income tax rates by one percentage
point as part of a giant tax cut they hope to tout to voters over
the August recess.
</P>
<P>
-- The captured Kurdish rebel chief, Abdullah Ocalan, ordered
his guerrillas Tuesday to end their armed campaign for self-rule
in Turkey's largely Kurdish southeastern region.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President B.J. Habibie of Indonesia officially accepted the
results of a Parliamentary election on June 7. The move ends
nearly two months of delays and squabbling by elections officials.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Potentially harmful chemicals should be tested further to
see what damage they may be doing to humans, says a report by
divided federal panel that is likely to influence research funding.
Scientists appear concerned about chemicals that affect hormone
production.
</P>
<P>
-- Japan is trying to curb the yen's advance by suggesting that
the U.S. might join its efforts. The tactic sent the dollar
higher against the yen. 
