<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seals Off Hebron after Shooting Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers sealed off a
divided Hebron in West Bank Wednesday after two Jewish settlers
were wounded in an ambush possibly carried out by Palestinian
militants overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers imposed a curfew on the Israeli-controlled
part of the city and set up roadblocks around the city, barring
Palestinians from entering and leaving the city.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers also carried out home searches and questioned
people.
</P>
<P>
Two settlers were lightly wounded when unidentified gunmen
opened fire on them Tuesday night while they were driving through
the downtown on the way home in the Jewish settlement of Tel
Romeida in the heart of a Palestinian neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The shooting was the first incident of its kind since
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak took office early last month.
</P>
<P>
Barak has warned of such terror attacks as the troubled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process moves forward.
</P>
<P>
Barak issued a statement Wednesday condemning the "very
serious attack" and demanding that the Palestinian National
Authority "act with the greatest determination" to capture the
militants.
</P>
<P>
Hebron is a flash-point of conflict between Israel and the
Palestinians since more than 400 Jewish settlers live among
120,000 Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
According to an interim accord signed by the Palestinian and
Isreal in 1997, Israel handed over 80 percent of the city to the
Palestinians but retains control over the rest part.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident also came as Israel and the Palestinians
are at odds over the implementation of the U.S.-brokered Wye
agreement, which was frozen by Barak's hard-line predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu last year.
</P>
<P>
Pledging to reach a comprehensive peace in the region in
about 15 months, Barak has promised to carry out the remaining
two stages of the interim agreement.
</P>
<P>
But he has been seeking to make some changes to the
implementation, proposing to postpone the final stage till after
the final-status talks is well under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have repeatedly turned down his idea, urging
him to carry out the agreement in full.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media also revealed earlier this week that Barak is
planning to put off the beginning of the troop withdrawal
stipulated by the agreement until October 1.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Jerusalem Post said Wednesday that U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is weighing postponing a
scheduled regional tour because Washington is unhappy with Barak's
proposed delay in the implementation of the accord.
</P>
<P>
If Albright were indeed to delay her visit, set for next
week, it would be a setback for Barak, who has viewed the
trip as the key to an early resumption of talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Albright wants to see real progress on both the Syrian
and Palestinian tracks before she comes to visit, the Haaretz
daily said.
</P>
<P>
Washington does not intend to get involved in the current
Israeli-Palestinian dispute over the implementation of the Wye
accord, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
