<HEADLINE> Taiwan Explanation on "Special State-to-State Relations" Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Taiwan Work
Office of the CPC Central Committee and the Taiwan Affairs Office
of the State Council today refuted the Taiwan authorities' written
explanation on "special state-to-state relations".
</P>
<P>
The official said the "Mainland Affairs Council" of the Taiwan
authorities issued a so-called "written explanation on special
state-to-state relations" on August 1.
</P>
<P>
He said Lee Teng-hui did not dare to openly advocate his "two-
states" statement amid strong criticism by Chinese people
worldwide and the pressure of the reiteration by the international
community of the "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
So Lee tried to propagate "special state-to-state relations"
instead, in a bid to continue deceiving Taiwan people and the
international community, and his final target is still the "two
states" statement.
</P>
<P>
The official said the written explanation insisted that the two
sides of the Taiwan Straits have been divided into two states, and
China's sovereignty and territory have been cut apart based on Lee
's remarks.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the official said, the Taiwan authorities wanted to
cover up the splittist nature of their "two-states" statement with
the so-called "special characteristics."
</P>
<P>
As is known to all that the government of the People's Republic
of China is the only legitimate government for the whole of China,
and during cross-straits negotiations several basic points must be
insisted upon, that is, there is only one China in the world and
Taiwan is part of China, and China's sovereignty and territory can
not be split up, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the insistence upon the "two-states" statement is a
challenge to China's sovereignty and territorial integrity, and a
challenge to the practical and long-term interest of the Taiwan
compatriots and to the peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
This act will be severely punished by history, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
