<HEADLINE> Subway Fire Kills Two in Azerbaijan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A fire in a subway station in the
Azerbaijani capital of Baku early Wednesday killed two workers and
injured four others, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The fire was believed to be set off by a welding operation at
the Meshadi Azizbekov station, Itar-Tass reported in a dispatch
from Baku, quoting Azad Samedov, deputy chief of the fire
department of Azerbaijan's Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The two dead workers are still being identified. Doctors of
the country's toxicology center are treating the four other
wounded, who were listed in grave conditions.
</P>
<P>
The fire has partially paralyzed the subway services with
trains operating only to the Narimanov station, about four
kilometers from city center. All stations in the residential
areas are closed, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's fire was the second one that hit the Baku subway
system since October, when a fire in the tunnel linking Ulduz and
Narimanov stations killed 289 people and injured about 200. The
fire was caused by a short circuit in a safety lock, Itar-Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Baku metro system was also rocked by two explosions in
March and July. A total of 33 persons were killed and more than 50
wounded in those blasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
