<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader in Egypt for Talks on Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi
arrived in Egypt Wednesday for talks with President Hosni Mubarak
on bilateral relations and Libya's efforts to restore normal ties
with the rest of the world after seven years of U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi crossed into Egypt's border town of Salloum earlier in
the day and was greeted at the border crossing point by Governor
of Matrouh Governorate Kamel Amer, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
This was Gaddafi's first trip to Egypt since April after Libya
handed over two suspects in the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988. The explosion killed 270 people, most
of them American or British.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will meet Gaddafi in the Mediterranean town of Mersa
Matrouh, 550 kilometers northwest of Cairo, the news agency said.
Mubarak arrived in the town earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to urge Gaddafi to press the implementation
of the joint ventures in the fishery industry and land reclamation
deals, which were agreed on during the Libyan leader's Egyptian
visit in March.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are also expected to discuss trade ties,
Gaddafi's efforts to convene an extraordinary African summit in
Tripoli next month, and efforts to lift the U.N. sanctions on
Libya instead of suspending.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council suspended the sanctions,
including an international flight ban, in April following Libya's
handover of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi came to Egypt by road instead of by plane as the
neighbors' air traffic remains frozen in their strained relations.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi has accused Egypt and other Arab countries of doing too
little to support him in the confrontation with the West over the
Lockerbie issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
