<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes U.N. Committee for Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Wednesday criticized the
U.N. Sanctions Committee for blocking contracts Iraq signed with
foreign companies under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A total of 457 Iraqi contracts worth 756 million U.S. dollars
signed under the fifth phase of the oil-for-food program are still
blocked by the U.N. Sanctions Committee, said an Iraqi Trade
Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said in a statement carried by the Iraqi
News Agency that Iraq held American and British representatives in
the United Nations committee of responsible for hampering the
endorsement of those contracts.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the continuation of hampering the contracts
revealed the aggressive policy pursued by the United States and
Britain toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that those contracts comprise 95 for the industrial
sector and 72 for the health sector while the other contracts
cover the sectors of transport, oil, commerce, water and sewage,
irrigation, higher education and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to export limited
amount of oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the amount
of oil Iraq is allowed to export has been raised to 5.2 billion
dollars from 2 billion dollars for the first three phases.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated Iraq's demand for putting an end to
the stringent embargo and that the oil-for-food deal should not be
exploited to prolong the embargo imposed on the country following
its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
