<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Container Shipping Booming in South China Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The latest statistics indicate
that the Shenzhen Container Port in south China's Guangdong
Province is experiencing a prosperous period.
</P>
<P>
It has entered the world's top 20 ranks for related facilities
and transport capacity. Last year, it gained a 19th-place ranking,
based on a vigorous year-on-year growth rate of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The growth momentum continued during the first half of this
year, with the port handling 1.28 TEU (ton equivalent unit)
containers, up 64.2 percent on the previous year's same period.
</P>
<P>
The port's booming business is attributed to the improved
numbers and operations of its international regular shipping
routes, which both rank first in China.
</P>
<P>
So far, 21 of the world's most prestigious shipping companies
have opened 33 regular shipping routes to the port. An average of
109 cargo ships berth at the port per month.
</P>
<P>
The port's throughput increased from 179,000 tons in 1994 to 1.
95 million last year, and the figure is expected to reach three
million by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
