<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Asks Paging Companies to Re-register </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Information
Industry (MII) and the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce (SAIC) released a notice recently asking paging providers
to re-register in order to put an end to serious radio
communications disturbances by paging services affecting aircraft
and sea communications.
</P>
<P>
Paging stations with working frequencies in accord with state
demand, and having approval from related departments, can re-
register in industry and commerce administration departments.
</P>
<P>
Those causing continued disturbance to the aircraft navigation
systems and over-water communications after technical upgrading
will be closed.
</P>
<P>
Those with working frequencies conflicting with state rules
will also be closed, said the notice.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiujun, a MII official, noted that the increasing number
of paging stations, the irrational locations of paging service
providers, and poor equipment have all contributed to the
disturbance of normal air traffic and over-water communications.
</P>
<P>
In August 1997, Shenzhen Airport was closed for two hours
because of electromagnetic disturbance from paging stations.
Similar hazards also occurred at the Beijing International Airport.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has witnessed the rapid development of
paging services, and by the end of this June, the country had
over 1,763 paging companies and more than 72 million pager users.
</P>
<P>
"But one-third of the providers are too small, and there are
too many of them," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang added that the MII encourages mergers among paging
companies, and that this should be the future direction for China'
s paging industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
