<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80 Pigs Died of Swine Fever in S. Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 80 pigs in Mozambique's
Maputo Province have died of African swine fever, while 220 are
infected with the disease since March this year.
</P>
<P>
Americo Conceicao, head of the Provincial Animal-farming
Services, revealed this here Tuesday, warning that tens of
thousands of pigs will be lost if no precautions are made, the
Noticias newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first case of swine fever was discovered in the pig farm in
the veterinary faculty in the University of Eduardo Mondlane. The
epidemic then spread to the suburban areas of capital Maputo and
nearby cities.
</P>
<P>
Swine fever broke out in the province in 1995 when the
pig-farming industry in southern Mozambique was almost destroyed.
</P>
<P>
African swine fever is very infectious with a strong resistant
virus. It could be infectious through blood, saliva, dung, dead
body, equipment and water. Once infected, blue spots can be
detected on the pig within four to 24 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
