<HEADLINE> Malaysia Expects 2-3 Percent GDP Growth for 2nd Quarter 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's gross domestic
product (GDP) for the second quarter of this year could grow by
between 2.0 and 3.0 percent, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is definitely going to be plus and not minus, between 2.0
and 3.0 percent, he told reporters after launching the second
National Economic Consultative Council (NECC II).
</P>
<P>
The 2-3 percent growth projection is a clear indication that
Malaysia's economy is recovering after a painful recession last
year when it contracted by 7.5 percent and by a lesser margin of
1.3 percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank Negara (state bank) said that the country was
already out of recession judging from the GDP growth of 1.4
percent recorded in the February to March period this year
compared with the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's quick recovery was attributed to the National
Economic Recovery Plan which stimulated business activity and to
the selective capital controls which insulated the economy from
financial instability.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of a massive outflow of funds from September
1, 1999 when the levy on the repatriation of foreign capital
expires, Mahathir said, "If they want to take their money out we
allow that."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia however has generated enough international reserves to
withstand the outflow, he said, adding his government had taken
measures to attract long-term foreign investments into the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
