<HEADLINE> Cape Verde to Conquer Poverty, Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Cape Verde Prime Minister Carlos
Verga acknowledged Tuesday that his country is suffering torments
from poverty, unemployment and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made before deputies of the National Assembly or
parliament,

Verga said his country feels bad as it is "disturbed by some
ailments".
</P>
<P>
The country's unemployment rate hit 26 percent last year while
the rural people, accounting for 80 percent of the nation's
population, were tormented by poverty, malnutrition and bad
health. Meanwhile, drug using and trafficking became serious
problems in Cape Verde, according to Verga's speech.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will make efforts to improve the
economic and financial situation as well as education and judicial
justice.
</P>
<P>
Verga also mentioned the progress made by the government last
year, in the fields of social politics, education, health
infrastructure, citizens' rights, local finance and culture as
well as creating conditions for the officialization of the Cape
Verde language.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has accepted a new concept of basic
necessities, with its investment in social sectors accounting for
40 percent of public investment and constituting a major slice of
investment of the budget.  
</P>
