<HEADLINE> Baby Tigers in Good Health After Cesarean Birth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The three baby Siberian tigers
which were successfully delivered through a Cesarean section over
a month ago are in good health.
</P>
<P>
The 11-year-old mother tiger, "Erhuan," was considered too old
for labor in a natural birth, having been pregnant twice before
and giving birth to stillborns.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth birth of the baby tigers, veterinarians at
a local hospital decided to perform a Cesarean on her, the first
such operation to be performed on a tiger.
</P>
<P>
Nine dogs served as wet nurses for the three cub tigers after
their birth, and the young tigers are now gaining weight and
becoming stronger by the day, according to attendants at the city
zoo.
</P>
<P>
"The tiger cubs will be released into the jungles to adapt to
life in the wild when they grow older," said one attendant.
</P>
<P>
Listed as an endangered species by the World Wildlife Fund, the
Siberian tiger has been declining in number due to a deteriorating
natural environment, and only about 200 of them are now found in
China, less than 20 living in the wild. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
