<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, U.S.  Lift Visa Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government and the
United States of America have lifted visa acquisition in a bid to
strengthen the existing bilateral relationship between the two
countries, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The move will be effective immediately, the U.S. government
can issue ten-year, multiple-entry, no fee visas to Rwanda
citizens who qualify for a U.S visa," U.S Ambassador to Rwanda
George Staples was quoted as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Rwandans still must pay 45 U.S. dollars application fee and
must still meet the qualifications set forth in the U.S
immigration law," he further noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, a visa gives a traveler permission to request
entry to the U.S. The immigration officer at the port of entry
will authorize the length of stay which is usually six months for
tourism or business trips.
</P>
<P>
"Travelers must request an extension from the department of
immigration in the U.S for stays beyond six months," Staples
indicated.
</P>
<P>
Applications for student visas must submit an original 1-20
form issued by educational institution, proof of funds available
to pay for one's studies and English language skills.
</P>
<P>
"Submission of fraudulent documents may result in permanent
ineligibility for a visa," Staples confirmed.
</P>
<P>
In the cabinet meeting held at the end of last month,
Vice-President Major General Paul Kagame said Rwanda will also
give free entry visas to their American counterparts who wish to
visit Rwanda for tourism and business.
</P>
<P>
Donald Kaberuka, Minister of Finance and Economic Planning,
highlighted that Rwanda appreciated the bilateral relationship
existing between the two countries through visa rifting and
open-sky agreements where aircraft fly freely in and out of the
two states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
