<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity Charges Up by 25 Percent in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Electricity Regulatory
Board (ERB) has announced the rise in electricity charges by
between 10 to 25 percent as from August 1.
</P>
<P>
Chief Power Engineer Kevin Kariuki told Xinhua Wednesday that
electricity charges range between 1.55 shillings per kilowatt-hour
(kwh) for those consuming less than 50 units to 13.80 shillings
for the consumption of between 3,001 and 7,000 units.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the 1.55 shillings per kwh is a life-line
rate specially for the needed, and that's why the electricity
charges differ greatly.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by the Regulatory Board, its Chairman
Moses Wetangula said domestic consumers would now pay a fixed
charge of 75 shillings (one U.S. dollar) a month.
</P>
<P>
However, the rate for off peak hours has gone down to encourage
heavy electricity users to opt for low rate production hours and
ease the load on the national power supply.
</P>
<P>
Large commercial and industrial consumers will now pay six
shillings per kwh and a low rate of three shillings per kwh
depending on supply voltage.
</P>
<P>
Wetangula said 144 industrial concerns including the largest
electricity consumers and individuals were called by the board to
a public hearing to air their views about the proposed tariff
increase.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Power and Lighting Company wanted a rise in charges in
order to make the power sub-sector attractive to private sector
investors and provide resources for expanding power generation,
transmission and distribution capacity, said the chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
