<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Issues Presidential Decree to Confirm Poll Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
has issued a presidential decree to confirm the results of the
June 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
"The decree is dated August 4, 1999," State Secretary/Justice
Minister Muladi said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Muladi said the president had to make a decision on the legal
status of the poll results, which have drawn controversy after 27
of the 48 political parties refused to sign them due to alleged
election fraud.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1999 General Election Law, if less than two-thirds of
the General Elections Committee (KPU) members sign, the results
cannot be declared officially valid.
</P>
<P>
The KPU, which include representatives from the 48 political
parties and five government representatives, handed over the case
to the head of state for a decision.
</P>
<P>
In an informal meeting with leaders of political parties which
won seats in the House of Representatives (DPR) and KPU leaders
Tuesday, Habibie said he has approved the poll results.
</P>
<P>
Muladi said the decree concerns the legalization of the
election results based on a certificate of tabulation on the vote
count submitted by the district election committees, provincial
election committees and the KPU.
</P>
<P>
The decree also asks the KPU and the Indonesian Election
Committee (PPI) to continue observing the various stages of the
election process until the general session of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president. It will
comprise the DPR members plus 200 appointed regional and interest
groups' representatives. The House itself will have 500 members,
462 of whom will come from the 48 political parties that contested
the election. The remaining 38 members will be military personnel
and policemen appointed by the Armed Forces leadership.
</P>
<P>
The PPI concluded the vote count on July 15, giving the bulk of
the 462 seats at stake to five major parties. The main opposition
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) won with 33.74
percent of votes, outnumbering the ruling Golkar Party, which
trailed with 22.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trailing in third place is the National Awakening Party with
12.61 percent, followed by the United Development Party (10.71
percent) and the National Mandate Party (7.12 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
