<HEADLINE> Maradona, Kempes Set Sight on Chinese Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Argentina soccer star
Diego Maradona might make his comeback to competition for the
fourth time as he expressed his wish to be a coach-player in
soccer-crazy China.
</P>
<P>
Another heavyweight Mario Kempes, who led Argentina to the 1978
World Cup champions, also took fancy to Chinese soccer and made no
secret of his willingness to coach a club of the 14-team Chinese
professional soccer league, according to the Chines Sports Daily
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kempes, who paid his first visit to China with his agent
Horacio Fernandez last week, used the term "shock" to describe his
feeling about Chinese professional soccer league, which was
initiated six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Maradona did not know their visit until Kempes was leaving here
but he managed to get in touch with Fernandez through Beijing-
based Argentina Embassy to China, showing his willingness to play
and coach here.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez, who was also the agent of Maradona, stressed that
Maradona, 38, planned his return to soccer in China not for the
sake of money but for his liking for the Chinese soccer atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Maradona, who led Argentina to the title of the 1986 World Cup
and finished runners-up at the 1990 Italy World Cup, had been
idolized by Chinese soccer fans for his unmatched skills.
</P>
<P>
During his spell with Boca Junior club of Argentina, the soccer
star paid his first visit to China in 1996 and played two matches
with local teams.
</P>
<P>
Maradona had managed to recover from a 15-month suspension from
the Italian league in the late 1980's and a second ban during the
1994 World Cup. However he failed doping test in 1997 which made
his later comeback short-lived and put an end to his playing
career.
</P>
<P>
Maradona tried the role of coach-player in Argentina after the
end of his playing career but it turned out to be unsuccessful.
</P>
</TEXT>
