<HEADLINE> China's Border Town to Host World Women's Volleyball Grand Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The one million U.S. dollars
World Volleyball Grand Prix finals for women will be held at Yuxi,
Yunnan Province in southwestern China later this month, organizers
announced here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Prix, the most expensive women's tournament ever
organized by the volleyball's world governing body FIVB, features
eight top teams around world, including the current title holder
Brazil, last year's world championships and 1996 Olympics winner
Cuba, "the eternal runner-up" China and European powerhouse Russia.
</P>
<P>
Cha Dalin, Deputy Mayor of Yuxi told the press conference that:
"Yuxi has contributed 400,000 U.S. dollars to bring the finals to
this tiny border town, known for its honorable citizen Nie Er, the
composer of China's national anthem."
</P>
<P>
The elimination phase of the FIVB World Grand Prix is slated
for August 13-22 in Macao, Genting in Malaysia, Fong San in China'
s Taiwan Province, Manila in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
From August 13-15, China, Brazil, Italy and the Netherlands
will face off in Macao; while Cuba, Russia, Japan and South Korea
will be battling in Genting.
</P>
<P>
From August 20-22, Fong San is to host China, Russia, Japan and
the Netherlands; while Manila will set the scene for Cuba, Brazil,
Italy and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The semifinals (August 28) and final (August 29) are scheduled
to take place in Yuxi, where the best three teams from the
elimination phase plus host China will compete for the top honor.
</P>
</TEXT>
