<HEADLINE> Civilian Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese civilian was killed
and an army soldier wounded Wednesday morning in south Lebanon
during conflicts between Israeli forces and Lebanese guerrillas,
security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a truck driver was killed by a roadside bomb
while travelling to Naqoura in the western sector of the
Israel-occupying border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There have been no groups claiming responsibility for the
bombing. Roadside bomb attacks, however, were usually adopted by
Lebanese guerrillas in fighting against Israeli troops and the
pro-Israel South Lebanon Army in the area.
</P>
<P>
Also in the day, a Lebanese soldier was wounded in an Israeli
shelling near the Hamra crossing point south of Tyre, the
country's southern coastal city.
</P>
<P>
The incidents raised to 18 the number of civilians killed in
south Lebanon since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that Israeli warplanes struck suspected
guerrilla targets in south Lebanon by firing air-to-surface
missiles in an apparent response to earlier attacks launched by
the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of casualties or damages in the
raid which has been confirmed by Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli and the SLA out of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
