<HEADLINE> Indian Research Body Sets Patents Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Scientific and
Industrial Research (CSIR) has set a goal of filing at least 1,000
Indian patents every year from 2001.
</P>
<P>
CSIR Director General R. A. Mashelkar said Wednesday that the
ambitious agenda, envisioned in the wake of fierce global
competition on Intellectual Property Rights (IPR), will be met by
CSIR's chain of 40 national laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The biggest R &AMP; D network of the country, CSIR is the first
organization to make an explicit IP policy statement aimed at
maximizing the benefits of the council from its intellectual
capital through a four-pronged strategy.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy is to stimulate higher levels of innovation
through a judicious system of rewards, ensure timely alliances for
enhancing the IP value," Mashelkar said.
</P>
<P>
The council aims to hold a portfolio of more than 500 foreign
patents by 2001 to enable alliances with global technological
leaders and generate at least five percent of its R &AMP; D budget
from IP licensing, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
