<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Rural Credit Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
today announced a new set of regulations governing the management
of small loans to farmers by rural credit cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the PBOC, the country's central bank, said that
this new move aims at improving the services of rural credit
cooperatives, increase credit for rural households and
agricultural production, and simplify loan procedures.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, small loans to farmers are
defined as short-term loans of limited amount and are secured by
the farmers' credit.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations say these loans must be used for crop
planting, animal husbandry, and other agricultural production, or
for private economies that serve agricultural production, farm
equipment and machinery, or for small-scale water conservation
projects.
</P>
<P>
Those using the loans must be local households or self-employed
individuals with a good credit record and a steady income.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said this procedure is a practical step toward
solving the farmers' difficulties in obtaining loans, and is
expected to provide timely and convenient financial support to
agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Forms New Council to Formulate Development Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday announced
the formation of a new National Economic Consultative Council to
formulate the country's new socio-economic policy for the first
decade of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Second National Economic Consultative Council (NECC II)
launched here by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad is designed to be
a crucial part of the process of formulating Malaysia's national
development policy covering the 2000-2010 period.
</P>
<P>
The NECC II will evaluate the performance of the National
Development Policy (NDP) drawn up for the 1991-2000 period and
will help shape a new policy which will steer national development
after 2000.
</P>
<P>
The new council is made up of 155 members representing
Malaysians of all races, from all levels of society and from
various walks of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
