<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Economy not Likely to Grow in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian economy is not likely
to grow in real terms in 1999, a economist has said.
</P>
<P>
Meebelo Mutukwa, former general manager for Gavmont Merchant
Bank, said this is because the productive sectors remain under
siege from the tripartite difficulties of fierce competition from
imports, high and rising domestic costs and a shrinking market,
making stagflation a reality.
</P>
<P>
This was drawn from strategic considerations for Zambia's
agriculture sector in light of liberalization and globalization,
Financial Mail newspaper Wednesday quoted Mutukwa as saying at the
recent 94th Zambia National Farmers Union Congress held in capital
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Mutukwa said he is perplexed with the sunny optimism Zambians
have continued to display in light of the persistent contraction
of the productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
"We have in our collective consciousness, attached our future
expectations of future prosperity to the privatization of the
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), the flood of foreign
investment, the resumption of heavy drops of aid from donor
countries."
</P>
<P>
This should not be the case as a significant portion of new
investment into the mines will be book entries as over 90 percent
of the capital expenditure will be for imported machinery, spares
and expertise, said the economist.
</P>
<P>
He also said logistical difficulties ranging from time lags in
obtaining licenses, permits, serviced land telephone lines, low
effective market demand given the low and failing real incomes of
the Zambian consumer, more attractive tax and duty incentives in
neighboring countries and lack of resolution to critical issues
pose serious questions to the basis of optimism.
</P>
<P>
Mutukwa, however, said he was happy to note that the export
enclaves such as horticulture, floriculture, coffee and tobacco
under specific schemes that are significantly funded by
multilateral and bilateral funds at rational rates of interest
with repayment periods longer than one season have achieved
impressive results.
</P>
<P>
"This growth must be assessed further in the context of
international market access and reasonable price realization," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mutukwa also called on Zambian companies to focus on achieving
economies of scale through expansion or collaboration where they
could pull basic infrastructural to transport facilities to avoid
expenses on intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
In this way, optimal results would be achieved, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
