<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Eyes Ban on Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that he is considering imposing a complete
ban on illegal logging in central Rizal province after a landslide
hit a subdivision there Tuesday night and killed at least eight
persons.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a radio interview that this would be a
stop-gap measure while his administration carries out long-term
solutions to prevent the recurrence of similar disasters in the
future.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that without a massive reforestation and tree
planting program, the dredging and cleaning of drainage systems
would not be of much help to prevent flooding.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operations continue at the Cherry Hills
subdivision in Antipolo city, where about 50 houses were destroyed
by a landslide Tuesday night as heavy rains which started Sunday
continued pelting Metro Manila and nearby provinces.
</P>
<P>
A report of the Presidential Palace said that 10 residents of
the collapsed subdivision are still missing, while 28 people have
been rescued in the debris and about 200 survivors were evacuated
to a nearby church.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado rushed to the scene Wednesday
morning to supervise the massive search and rescue operation
performed mainly by the Armed Forces of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government said that flash floods on Luzon
Island starting Sunday have killed at least 35 people, submerged
nearly 300 villages and affected more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada declared Tuesday a state of
calamity in Metro Manila and the provinces of Pangasinan, Pampanga
and Rizal and ordered the release of 440 million pesos (11 million
U.S. dollars) from the calamity fund.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all government agencies to coordinate search,
rescue and relief operations to ensure the safety of residents in
the affected areas and safeguard the properties of residents who
abandoned flooded homes.
</P>
<P>
Edmundo Larroza, officer-in-charge of the Philippine National
Police (PNP), warned Wednesday hoarders, profiteers and other
unscrupulous traders refrain from taking advantage of the ongoing
calamity situation.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some unscrupulous traders in these areas
have hiked prices of basic commodities by as much as 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological authorities predict that monsoon rains will
still prevail over the western sections of Luzon Island in the
next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
