<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 29 Public Firms Sold in Tanzania: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania sold 29 public
firms, earning 57.38 million U.S. dollars last year, Minister of
State Nassoro Malocho has said.
</P>
<P>
The government had planned to divest 50 firms last year, but
sales agreement were concluded for only 29, Malocho told the
National Assembly or parliament in the central city Dodoma
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue to divest the state-owned firms
through the Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission at a
rate of 50 a year, The African Wednesday quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The privatization exercise, however, has been affected by heavy
 indebtedness of some parastatals.
</P>
<P>
"Many firms are in the red, unable to pay salaries to employees
and have huge liabilities," he said. "This scares away investors."
</P>
<P>
By last December, 270 out of 395 public firms scheduled for
divestiture have been sold and the remaining 125 are at different
stages of privatization.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to divest parastatal companies to create
more jobs and enhance national income.
</P>
<P>
The firms cover telecommunications, harbors, water and
sanitation, as well as petroleum refinery and railway sectors.
</P>
<P>
The government has agreed with World Bank and International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to remove 50 companies from government control
annually.
</P>
<P>
During July 1997 to June 1998, a total of 52 companies and nine
non-core entities were divested, according to figures released by
the Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
