<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Drinking Water Source Well Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The people of Hong Kong are now
reassured of the quality of the water they drink everyday, since a
recent survey showed that the water piped in through Shenzhen, a
neighboring boom town, is much clearer than ever.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong depends for 70 percent of its fresh water on
Dongjiang River water that comes in from Shenzhen in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
This latest water-quality report from the State Environmental
Protection Administration suggests that the quality of water
sampled from the river's mainstream can be classified as at the
national first and second degree level.
</P>
<P>
Peng Zhiliang, director of the Southwest China Environment
Research Institute under the administration, told Xinhua that the
river is actually one of the most well-protected in China.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the quality of reservoir water in
Shenzhen has been improved by a wide margin because of
environmental protection efforts made by the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The swelling population and fast urban construction in Zhujiang
River Delta area in Guangdong has contributed to growing water
contamination in the Dongjiang River.
</P>
<P>
The area was a large stretch of fertile farmland until the
1980s, but has been quickly developed and exploited because of its
proximity to Hong Kong, and the population has grown to more than
one million from some 100,000 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has reacted quickly to introduce
regulations and policies to deal with environmental problems in
this rapidly developing region. On the 83-km-long water conduit to
Hong Kong, there are now seven sewage treatment plants, including
several large facilities, with the combined daily capacity to
treat 115,000 tons sewage.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has used 280 million yuan to build a biochemical
sewage-treatment plant, which will come on line by year's end.
</P>
<P>
Silt dredging in Shenzhen reservoir also will be carried out
later this year. This project will take three years to remove one-
million cubic meters of sludge in the reservoir bed to reduce
organic pollutant in the water.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is working with Shenzhen on replacing outdated pipes
from 1964 to further reduce contamination, a project that is
expected to be completed by 2002 at a cost of five billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Efforts to Fight Low-price Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Planning
Commission (SDPC), China's price watchdog, has intensified efforts
to fight low-price dumping activities by issuing a 20-article
regulation.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation aims to crack down on low-price dumping,
rampant in recent years in business activities, in an attempt to
maintain a fair market for price competition, an SDPC official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is also necessary to enable relevant departments
and localities to use legal means in exercising macroeconomic
controls, safeguard the State's interests as well as the rights
and interests of businesses and consumers, stimulate domestic
demand, and lift the state-owned enterprises out of difficulties
within three years, the official added.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC, along with other governmental departments, had
already adopted several measures to prevent low-price dumping in
the industrial sector, and these efforts have paid off.
</P>
<P>
Low-price dumping began spreading as market competition became
stronger, the official said, stressing that the new regulation
will cover any low-price dumping activity in all areas.
</P>
<P>
The Price Law already states that low-price dumping activities
are illegal. This new regulation further differentiated between
dumping and reasonable price cuts.
</P>
<P>
The country's overall price indexes have been declining for
more than 20 months now, a result of sluggish demand. That's why
the SDPC is taking these measures to straighten out price
violations, the official concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Turkish Soldiers' Release Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said on Wednesday that he hoped the two Turkish soldiers
held by Iran would be freed within "the next several days."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the remark when asked to comment on repeated
Turkish requests for the release of the two soldiers, reportedly
captured on July 22 when Turkish forces tried to cross into Iran's
West Azarbaijian province, the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Their speedy release will be "a sign of Iran's good offices,"
Kharrazi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
This appeared to be the result of talks between Kharrazi and
his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem on the sidelines of the recent
Balkan summit in Sarajevo, during which the two sides reportedly
reached certain understanding in solving their rows.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that during the talks, Cem told him that the two
soldiers had violated the Iranian border unintentionally and
called for the release of them.
</P>
<P>
Cem reaffirmed that his country had no ill-intention against
Iran, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish soldiers' arrests came five days after a border
incident between the two countries, in which four Turkish
warplanes bombed an Iranian border post and several villages,
killing five people and injuring 10 others.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkish troops were trying to crack down
on separatist Kurdish rebels seeking shelter in Iran. Upon
Tehran's demand, Turkey has sent an experts delegation to the
border area to investigate the air raids and compile a report.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds with each other on
many issues; but this time neither of them seems to want the
border incidents to poison their overall relationship.
</P>
<P>
Both have stressed the need for "common understanding" to
strengthen bilateral relations in all fields despite the incidents.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into account the humanitarian aspect of the issue and
in view of the assurances given by the Turkish foreign minister
and other officials that the violation of the border was not
deliberate, the Islamic Republic of Iran is positively considering
the issue (of releasing the soldiers)," Kharrazi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
