<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium on Ancient Chinese Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 263 Chinese and overseas
scholars and specialists today gathered in Jinan, capital of east
China's Shandong Province, to discuss the Book of Songs, one of
China's renowned five ancient classics.
</P>
<P>
The Book of Songs, China's earliest collection of poetry,
contains 305 verses on the politics, economy, war, religion, and
folkways of the Western Zhou Dynasty (11th century B.C.-771 B.C.)
and is of high historical and literary value.
</P>
<P>
Confucius (551 B.C.- 479 B.C.) is reputed to have worked on the
Book of Songs, and introduced it as a compulsory course for his
students; it has been part of Chinese higher education since the
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The Book of Songs has always been a topic for research in China,
and it was spread to overseas as early as 1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one specialists from Japan, the United States, the
Republic of Korea, and Singapore attended today's symposium, the
fourth of its kind.
</P>
<P>
The previous three were held in Shijiazhuang and Beidaihe, both
in north China's Hebei Province, and in Guilin, a scenic city in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The five classics are the Book of Songs, the Book of History,
the Book of Changes, the Book of Rites, and the Spring and Autumn
Annals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smog Getting Thicker in Riau, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Smog in Pekanbaru, provincial
capital of Indonesia's Riau, has become thicker Wednesday, causing
visibility in the city to drop to only 100 to 200 meters, reported
the Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The condition has forced the local people to wear masks and
motorists to turn on their lights while driving.
</P>
<P>
Most of the locals however preferred to stay at home, leaving
the streets deserted.
</P>
<P>
Antara quoted some people as saying that what has been
happening is similar to what had happened in 1997 when forest
fires raged in many parts of the islands of Sumatera and
Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
Ismanu, an official of the local communication office, said his
office has declared an emergency for land, sea and air
transportation.
</P>
<P>
The head of the local forestry and plantations office said the
smog has disrupted trips in the Malacca Strait.
</P>
<P>
The smog is dangerous to people's health, said Ekmal Rusdi,
head of the local health office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
