"The overall impact of the global economic situation on China's
exports will be positive next year," according to Song Qun of SDPC
's institute of foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Song added that China's export volume will experience a greater
increase in the latter half of this year, when measures such as
increased tax rebates and the intensified crackdown on smuggling
take effect.
</P>
<P>
He predicts that the export volume is likely to register an
annual decrease of less than 2 percent this year, and that trade
surplus will be around 15-20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's export volume hit 83.01 billion U.S. dollars in the
first half of this year, down 4.6 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Song pointed out, unfavorable factors still exist,
such as the enhanced trade protectionism of some Western countries.
</P>
<P>
He said optimistic prospect for larger exports to southeast
Asian countries was undermined by concerns that the rapid
appreciation of their currencies could negatively affect their
exports and decelerate the revitalization of their economies.
</P>
<P>
To offset these negative factors, Song suggests that China
further increase export tax rebates and credit, enhance efforts to
stem smuggling, and increase the number of private enterprises
allowed to engage in import and export commerce.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to transform the export structure by
increasing the proportion of value-added products in labor-
intensive industries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Song also predicts that China's imports will maintain upbeat
growth next year, due to required lifting of restrictions as a
condition for entry into the World Trade Organization. He
estimates that import growth will be some 10 percent higher than
this year's figure.
</P>
<P>
China's import volume hit 75.01 billion U.S. dollars in the
first half, up 16.6 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
