<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Landslide in Philippines Claims 3 More Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescue teams found three more dead
bodies Wednesday morning in the debris of houses destroyed Tuesday
night by a landslide in the central Philippines, the Philippine
News Agency (PNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
This brought to six the number of deaths in the tragic disaster
which struck a six-hectare subdivision in Antipolo city in Rizal
province. Earlier, three boys were confirmed dead on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The collapsed Cherry Hill subdivision had about 400 concrete
houses, more than 300 of which had been occupied, said PNA.
</P>
<P>
Antipolo Mayor Angelito Gatlabayan said about 50 houses were
destroyed by tons of earth and gravel which rumbled with
terrifying impact, destroying vehicles and houses in its path.
</P>
<P>
The Office of Civil Defense (OCD) feared that fifty people
might have been killed in this tragedy brought about by incessant
rain that flooded a wide area on Luzon Island.
</P>
<P>
The OCD said that it was the worst to happen since the flood
started last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Residents said as early as Tuesday morning, they observed some
cracks but it was only in the evening that the tragedy struck.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado rushed to the scene Wednesday
morning to supervise the massive search and rescue operation
performed mainly by the Armed Forces of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Heavy equipment, ambulances and rescue workers also rushed to
the scene.
</P>
<P>
PNA said that 28 people have been retrieved from the debris and
brought to the district hospital while about 200 survivors were
evacuated to a nearby church.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are looking for a certain Hiroshi Ogawa, a Japanese
who reportedly developed the subdivision.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government said that flash floods on Luzon
Island brought about by torrential rains starting Sunday have
killed at least 32 people, submerged nearly 300 villages and
affected more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada declared Tuesday a state of
calamity in Metro Manila and the provinces of Pangasinan, Pampanga
and Rizal and ordered the release of 440 million pesos (11 million
U.S. dollars) from the calamity fund.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all government agencies to coordinate search,
rescue and relief operations to ensure the safety of residents in
the affected areas and safeguard the properties of residents who
abandoned flooded homes.
</P>
<P>
Edmundo Larroza, officer-in-charge of the Philippine National
Police (PNP), warned Wednesday hoarders, profiteers and other
unscrupulous traders refrain from taking advantage of the ongoing
calamity situation.
</P>
<P>
He directed all PNP regional directors in areas threatened by
rising flood waters to closely monitor all public markets and
retail outlets to ensure that prices of basic commodities will
remain within price control levels.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some unscrupulous traders in these areas
have hiked prices of basic commodities by as much as 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological authorities predict that monsoon rains will
still prevail over the western sections of Luzon Island in the
next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
