<HEADLINE> Sydney Organizers Pressured to Change Athletics Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Sydney Organizing Committee
for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) was under pressure from the world
athletics ruling body to change the schedule for some of the most
popular track and field events.
</P>
<P>
The International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) told SOCOG
last week it now required a rest day between the semi-finals and
finals of events of 400 meters and longer and two days' break for
races of 3,000 meters and above.
</P>
<P>
This would not be an easy task for SOCOG for it could affect as
many as 13 events.
</P>
<P>
Sports Commission chairman John Coates said Wednesday the SOCOG
would try to adhere to the IAAF ruling if possible without
altering the dates of any finals.
</P>
<P>
"We're seeing if we can accommodate some of these policy
changes which are in the interest of the athlete ... without
changing the allocation of the finals."
</P>
<P>
International Olympic Committee Coordination Commission
chairman Jacques Rogge assured SOCOG in April that the IOC
executive board had the final say on Games scheduling and could
over-ride federations if any conflicts occurred.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has formally approved the entire Games schedule, while
the IAAF is the only federation yet to sign off on its program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Explores New Model for Flood Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China may establish a special
flood insurance organization in the near future, if a proposal by
experts is accepted by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made in a research report made available to
Xinhua by the Blanch and Swire Asia Co., Ltd., which sponsored the
research that began early this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the China Strategy and Management Research Society,
the Environmental Evolution and Natural Disaster Laboratory under
the Ministry of Education, Beijing Teachers University, and other
organizations contributed to the report.
</P>
<P>
China suffers the most frequent flooding of any country in the
world, occurring in all regions and causing greater economic
losses than any other natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid growth of the Chinese economy, losses caused by
floods have been increasing during this decade.
</P>
<P>
For example, China's annual losses from all natural disasters
amounted to about 50 billion yuan (about 6.03 billion U.S. dollars)
before the 1990s. But now, floods alone cause billions of dollars
in property losses every year.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, losses caused by the great
floods of last year were above 160 billion yuan (about 19.31
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
For many years, China has undertaken national mobilization
whenever severe floods occur, and experts say this has resulted in
a too heavy burden on the government resources and has greatly
disturbed normal national life.
</P>
<P>
They noted that if flood insurance were allowed to play a
greater role, the risk would be shared by the government,
enterprises, families, and insurance firms so that the entire
country would be much stronger and more efficient in the face of
the floods.
</P>
<P>
Flood damage is not independently insured in today's China, but
is one of the risks insured under comprehensive property liability
insurance.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the U.S., where the premium for flood insurance is
decided by the actual risk to the insured properties, China's
insurers charge a standard premium, which is the same as that for
fire risk.
</P>
<P>
Experts said this is not only unfair for both the insurers and
those insured, but also discourages the implementation of anti-
flood measures.
</P>
<P>
China also lacks a flood reinsurance system, which has
increased the risk to insurers in cases of severe flooding,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
They propose the establishment of special flood insurance to be
run by a commercial corporation, whose form is yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
They also suggest that the government should regard flood
insurance as a non-profit business, and therefore offer tax
benefits and other preferential policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Seize 44 Tons of Bhang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Police have seized 44.4
tons of bhang and arrested 27 suspects of illegal drug peddling
in a countrywide anti-drug operation.
</P>
<P>
The suspects, who were arrested in separate cases, included
three Nigerians, the Criminal Investigations Department (CID) of
the police revealed, according to Wednesday's Kenya Times
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Police said most of the suspects were caught while travelling
in buses from western Kenya to Kenyan capital Nairobi, where drugs
are believed to be smuggled to other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jackbam, head of the Anti-Narcotics Unit of the police,
urged bus operators to check passengers' baggages before loading
them to reduce the risk of the buses being held for illegally
transporting drugs.
</P>
<P>
Jackbam also said that his unit has launched an awareness
campaign on the danger of drug trafficking and abuse in secondary
schools.
</P>
<P>
Observers here hold that many high school students used drugs
in Kenya, posing a serous social problem.
</P>
<P>
Bhang, a kind of narcotics made from hemp, was reportedly
planted in Mount Kenya, the second highest mountain in Africa.
Kenyan police have destroyed a number of plantations there in a
bid to eradicate its production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
