<HEADLINE> China Initiating More Favorable Policies for Export Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China is committing itself to a
more favorable environment for its export-oriented companies by
reducing intermediary procedures and charges as well as lifting
restrictions on their trade, according to the State Economic and
Trade Commission (SETC).
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhigang, vice minister of SETC, said here today at a
working conference that China has raised the overall export rebate
rate by 5.51 percent this year, which is of crucial importance for
the export promotion.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 10,000 export companies in China with an
annual export volume of 40 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country will further implement its foreign trade reform,
and, by removing some restrictions on and certain procedures in
the export business, ease the burdens on export-oriented companies,
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government will give qualified domestic
manufacturers access to foreign engineering contracts and labor-
export businesses, and improve regulations on foreign trade such
as increasing quotas for brand-name products.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also said that a number of charges and fees in the export
process will be reduced or removed in favor of the export
companies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, financial institutions have given their support to
the export-oriented firms in terms of export credit, credit
insurance, and other financial instruments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing To Further Exploit Tourism Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Beijing plans to exploit new
scenic spots and tourism activities to attract more tourists from
both at home and abroad, according to municipal tourism
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital will further develop its tourism industry
by making good use of the conferences and business and trade
activities held in the city, and expand tourism by combining with
other industries including technology, culture, education, and
agriculture to employ both traditional and more recent historic
and scenic spots, and suburban resorts.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will also build a comprehensive domestic tourism market
by setting up cooperative relations with the provinces, other
cities, and nearby areas with abundant tourism resources.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that more and more investors and businesses
come to the city every year for trade negotiations and product
promotion, and this provides great opportunities to enhance the
local tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Tourism from abroad will focus on Japan, Taiwan, and western
European countries, Southeast Asia and the Republic of Korea, and
explore new markets in Russia, the Middle East, India, and South
America.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.05 million tourists visited Beijing in the first half of
this year, up 11.44 percent over the same period last year. The
growth rate for the number of tourists from Asia was 24 percent,
for America, 6.3 percent, Europe, 1.7 percent, Oceania, 5 percent;
while the number of visitors from Africa fell by 5.8 percent,
compared with the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 62.5 million overseas tourists came to China in 1998, up 8.
5 percent over 1997, and the figure for domestic travelers was 659
million, 2.4 percent more than in 1997 in spite of the impact of
the Asian financial crisis and serious flooding in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People Escape Poverty in South China's Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province will
redouble its efforts to help more poor residents pull out of
poverty in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent provincial meeting on poverty eradication,
the island province will spend 216 million yuan (about 26 million
U.S. dollars) this year to lift 100,000 poverty-stricken rural
residents out of their current plight, and increase their per
capita annual income by 300 yuan.
</P>
<P>
By next year, the number of the province's poor population will
be reduced from the current 223,000 to below 90,000, and per
capita income of local rural residents will climb to 1,000 yuan.
Hygienic tap water and electricity also will become available in
the province's remote villages, which will all be connected by
highways to central cities.
</P>
<P>
Hainan used to be a part of south China's Guangdong Province,
and became a province in its own right, and also the country's
largest special economic zone, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The island province, now with a population of six million, had
2.02 million people living under the poverty line of 300 yuan per
annum in 1987. In the past 11 years, it has spent 1.39 billion
yuan on poverty-relief work, bringing 1.79 million poor people out
of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the central government have
always given priority to solving the problem of basic needs for
the poor, whose numbers have diminished by 10 million annually, on
average, over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
At a recent national conference on poverty-relief, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin called on the nation to step up efforts to
resolve the basic problem of food and clothing for the country's
needy in the rural areas by next year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the impoverished population in the
rural areas dropped to 42 million from 250 million in 1978,
accounting for 4.6 percent of the total rural population, compared
with 30.7 percent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, China has inflated its poverty datum to 500
yuan per annum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
