<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Piano Manufacturer Competing On World Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Many people think that China
will become a global piano producer in five years and the world's
second largest piano company, the Zhujiang Piano Group in south
China's Guangdong Province may make this come true.
</P>
<P>
It was the second slot in piano sales last year, with its
modern computer-aided-design technology and advanced production
line and its capacity to produce 120,000 pianos annually. It has
50 percent of the domestic market and accounts for 40 percent of
China's piano exports. It sold 30,000 pianos in the first six
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
During a tour of the United States in February of this year,
Tong Zhicheng, chairman of the board of the group, found himself
surrounded by foreign sales reps and dealers who came to take a
look at their exhibit. But things were not so rosy just a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The piano has a 300-year history in the West, but Zhujiang,
which is considered an old company in China, only started business
in the 1950s, producing a mere dozen pianofortes a year. The
industry grew after the country's opening up and reforms and the
instrument became one of the primary choices of young music lovers.
By 1987, Zhujiang's output had just topped 10,000 units.
</P>
<P>
It expects to spend 500 million yuan on technology to improve
product quality to compete with the West and has invited prominent
piano specialists for consultation.
</P>
<P>
The company's eight new models presented last year brought in
65,000 orders at a presentation show.  
</P>
</TEXT>
