<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howard Reluctant to Change Republican Referendum Wording </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Wednesday appeared reluctant to change the republican
referendum question after a recommendation that the wording will
include a reference to replacing the Queen with an Australian head
of state.
</P>
<P>
Howard said in an interview that the government would examine
the recommendation when it is tabled in federal parliament Monday
and would then make up its mind.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation by a cross-party committee of MPs is at odds
with Howard's preference for current wording which focuses on the
selection of a president by a two-thirds majority of parliament,
and makes no mention of the Queen.
</P>
<P>
The new question proposes that "the Commonwealth of Australia
become a republic with the Queen and Governor-General to be
replaced by an Australian president."
</P>
<P>
Howard said the wording of the question should truthfully
reflect what was being put to the Australian people.
</P>
<P>
"It shouldn't contain words that, in a sense, prejudge the
issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The question itself should not be a vehicle for advancing one
or other side of the proposition," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
