<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Spill, One of Worst in Sydney Harbor History: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The latest oil spill in Sydney
Harbor was one of the worst in the harbor's history and an
international embarrassment, Australia's Total Environment Center
(TEC) Chief Executive Jeff Angel said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The spill occurred as the tanker Laura D'Amato unloaded its
cargo of light crude oil at Shell's Gore Bay terminal Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
"I've been down and examined the site this morning and there is
thick, black crude oil washing up on Berry Island Reserve, so it
is not evaporating, it is in fact recontaminating the site," Angel
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
"It's pretty embarrassing that the Olympic city can't in fact
boast that it has a clean and green harbor," he said.
</P>
<P>
The TEC would urge the government to examine a relocation plan
to get the Shell facility out of the harbor, he said.
</P>
<P>
The facility should be closer to emergency materials to lessen
the risk of another disastrous leak, he said.
</P>
<P>
Angel said that two coves in the immediate vicinity of the
harbor had been affected by the spill.
</P>
<P>
Gore Cove and Balls Head Bay were affected by crude oil lapping
back with the high tide, contaminating shell fish, crustaceans and
worms, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
