<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Chinese Encouraged To Help Protect Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua)-- The State Administration of
Cultural Heritage has new regulations that encourage overseas
Chinese to help with cultural relics protection.
</P>
<P>
The regulations are intended to protect the rights of overseas
donors and to ensure that their donations benefit China's cultural
relics protection, according to one official.
</P>
<P>
Overseas Chinese, international organizations, and funds that
help Chinese cultural relics protection can decide how their
donation is used, and to prevent interference with the donation.
</P>
<P>
People overseas have contributed a great deal in the first half
of the year and have helped finance the protection of the Mogao
Grottoes of Dunhuang and the 1,000-year-old Buddhist stone tablets
at Yunju Temple in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They have also helped rescue cultural relics that were smuggled
to foreign countries. Eighteen portraits of Buddhist saints from
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) and a gilded bronze statue of Buddha
from Dali, a kingdom of ancient China were bought back thanks to
overseas Chinese donations, this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Terminates Poorly-Performed Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday
terminated two special funds and reduced the allocation for
another due to their poor performance.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Adjustment Fund (IAF) and Special Scheme for Low
and Medium Cost Houses (SLMCH) were terminated with effect from
Wednesday, Bank Negara (state bank) announced.
</P>
<P>
The total allocation under the Rehabilitation Fund for Small
and Medium Industries (RFSMI) was reduced from 750 million ringgit
(197.368 million U.S. dollars) to 500 million ringgit (131.578
million U.S. dollars) also effective Wednesday, the central bank
said.
</P>
<P>
As of July 17, 1999, the IAF, which was launched in February
1991 with an allocation of 200 million ringgit (52.631 million
U.S. dollars), only saw 95 million ringgit (25 million U.S.
dollars) being disbursed while the SLMCH, which was launched in
May 1998 with an allocation of 1.0 billion ringgit (263.157
million U.S. dollars), saw only 168 million ringgit (44.21 million
U.S. dollars) being disbursed, it said.
</P>
<P>
The RFSMI, which was established in November last year with 750
million ringgit (197.368 million U.S. dollar) allocation, only saw
63 million ringgit (16.578 million U.S. dollars) being disbursed
as of July 17, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that to ensure an effective utilization
of the government's financial resources, the unutilized portion
from the IAF and the SLMCH as well as the 250 million ringgit
(65.789 million U.S. dollars) from the RFSMI will however be
rechanneled to the Fund For Small and Medium Industries (FSMI)
which has a higher utilization rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tourism Witnesses Strong Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of overseas tourists
coming to China and the income from their spending both enjoyed
double-digit growth in the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics from the National Tourism Administration
indicate that from January to June, the number of overseas
tourists to China surged 14.95 percent over the same period of
last year to hit 34.68 million.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China earned 6.91 billion U.S. dollars from
overseas tourism, up 15.94 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first half, tourists from 8 of China's 15 major
overseas markets, including Japan, the Republic of Korea, and
France, all saw double-digit growth, and the number of visitors
from Indonesia soared by 94.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
