<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The exodus of foreign capitals from Kenya slowed in
July as the market reacted to a new government reform plan that
put conservationist Richard Leakey to head the civil service.
</P>
<P>
Figures issued by Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) Tuesday showed
that net capital outflows by foreign investors dropped to 531,407
U.S. dollars in July from 1.34 million dollars in June. (Kenya-
Capital-Outflow)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank has released its first tranches to
Russia under its restructured structural adjustment loans, the
bank announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the World Bank's approval of the restructuring of the
second Coal Sector Adjustment Loan (Coal2) and the Social
Protection Adjustment Loan on July 23, and the third Structural
Adjustment Loan (SAL3), the bank disbursed 50 million U.S. dollars
under the Coal2 last Friday, and a further 100 million dollars on
Tuesday under SAL3, a bank statement said. (World Bank-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai cabinet endorsed a proposal on Tuesday to
strengthen economic cooperation between Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, raised by the Joint Committee between Thailand
and Vietnam on Economic Cooperation, urged both parties to promote
trade by eliminating trade barriers as much as possible. (Thailand-
Vietnam-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil and New Zealand signed an agreement here
Tuesday on technical cooperation to help promote trade in
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Brazilian Agriculture Minister
Marcus Vinicius Pratini de Moraes and John Luxton, his New Zealand
counterpart. (Brazil-New Zealand-Agricultural Deal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- An Argentine official on Tuesday accused the
World Trade Organization (WTO) of ignoring agricultural subsidies
made by the United States and other European governments.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Larreche, president of the National Institute of
Agricultural Technology, said he was going to prepare a complete
report on this issue to state the position of the Argentine
government in time for the WTO "Millennium Round" summit that
opens in the U.S. this November. (Argentina-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican Finance Secretary Jose Gurria said on
Tuesday that the country's financial market has become more stable
and mature, ruling out the possibility of a new economic crisis
due to the change in government next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Gurria made the assurance that
Mexico's stock prices and exchange rate will not fluctuate
drastically with changes in the political arena. (Mexico-Financial
Market) 
</P>
