<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Accuses WTO of Ignoring Agricultural Subsidies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An Argentine official on
Tuesday accused the World Trade Organization (WTO) of ignoring
agricultural subsidies made by the United States and other
European governments.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Larreche, president of the National Institute of
Agricultural Technology, said he was going to prepare a complete
report on this issue to state the position of the Argentine
government in time for the WTO "Millennium Round" summit that
opens in the U.S. this November.
</P>
<P>
"The WTO questions our statistical rates applied to the export
of some products, while the U.S. subsidizes soybean by 40 U.S.
dollars per ton. However, this organization (WTO) says nothing,"
Larreche said.
</P>
<P>
"And not to mention the European Union, which dedicates 350
billion dollars annually to subsidize agricultural products," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In the WTO, "they are very strict on some things, but not so
strict on others," he complained.
</P>
<P>
If the internal problems faced by rural producers of Argentina
are added to the "dirty tricks practiced by each country to
subsidize agricultural products, the situation would become
unbearable," Larreche said.
</P>
<P>
Warning that subsidies endanger the agriculture competitiveness
of South American countries, he said Argentina strongly calls for
a end to such practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA, AFC Confident over End to World Cup Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- FIFA president Sepp Blatter
revealed Tuesday his optimism that an Asian boycott of the 2002
World Cup could be avoided and the family of FIFA will be united.
</P>
<P>
Blatter, in Mexico for FIFA's Confederations' Cup, confirmed
that he had met Asian Football Confederation(AFC) secretary
general Peter Velappan here to discuss the issue, saying he was "
very confident that the family of FIFA will be united" before the
draw for the qualifying tournament in Tokyo on December 7.
</P>
<P>
Velappan said after the Blatter's news conference that AFC had
not given up its demand for an extra berth after Asia was just
allotted four spots, including two for the co-hosts Japan and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
But he said it is likely to reach an "amicable" solution to the
row.
</P>
<P>
"We are progressing with a lot of determination," Velappan said.
"Given the good will between all the parties we are very
optimistic."
</P>
<P>
The AFC has threatened to boycott the 2002 premier soccer event
if FIFA does not meet its demand and the entire delegation of AFC
walked out of a July FIFA congress in Los Angeles over the issue.
</P>
<P>
AFC has said it would decide in October whether to go ahead
with their boycott of the championship which is for the first time
to be staged in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insects Threatening Chinese Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A large number of insects have
damaged about 99.6 million mu (100 mu is 6.7 hectares) of forests
in China in the first half of this year, or 10 million mu more
than for the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
This is also 214 times the amount of forested area affected by
fires, according to Li Yuchai, the deputy director of the State
Forestry Administration. He says that this is 5 billion yuan (6.2
billion U.S. dollars) worth of damage every year. Not only forest
belts in 26 provinces and autonomous regions are destroyed but
also afforested areas of major cities, Li says.
</P>
<P>
The insects include the pine moth, weevils, and beetles, many
of which come in from foreign countries, and some newly planted
trees are especially vulnerable to them. There is also an
increasing number of tree seeds affected by disease.
</P>
<P>
Li has asked China to pay more attention to this and to
establish a monitoring system. China has 134 million hectares of
forest, but there are only 8.6 hectares for each Chinese on
average, compared to 71.8 hectares per capita on average in the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina to Host Mountaineering, Skiing Games of Military Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The seventh International
Competition of Mountain Troops and the 16th Military Skiing
Championship will be inaugurated on August 8 in Argentina, sources
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The games will take place from 9 to 13 of August in San Carlos
de Bariloche, Argentina's south-east province of Rio Negro, with
the participation of men's and women's teams representing the
armies of Argentina, Chile, Spain, the United States, Britain and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Military personnel from Peru, Paraguay and Uruguay will observe
the games.
</P>
<P>
The games consist of a biathlon of a 20-kilometer ski race and
a shooting range with moving targets using 22 carbine weapons.
</P>
<P>
There is also a group 25-kilometer race, with target shooting
and downhill slalom. 
</P>
