<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan Calls for Peace Talks in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Uzbekistan issued a statement
Tuesday calling on the conflicting parties in Afghanistan to end
military actions and resume peace talks, according to Interfax
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the latest rekindling of large scale
fighting in Afghanistan had fueled the tension in the country,
gravely hurt peacemaking efforts of the international community
and violated the Tashkent Declaration reached last week in the Six
Plus Two meeting.
</P>
<P>
The resort to force could not resolve the Afghanistan issue,
the statement said. It urged both sides to end military actions
and to return to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks were held on July 19, in Tashkent, the Uzbek
capital, involving the governing Taliban, an opposition alliance,
the U.N. special envoy for Afghanistan, Lakhdar Brahimi, and the
Six Plus Two group countries, which includes Afghanistan's six
neighbors -- China, Pakistan, Iran, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan and
Tajikistan -- as well as the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The participants signed a declaration, appealing to both Afghan
sides to end the war and realize national reconciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
