<HEADLINE> Official Says Mexican Financial Market Maturing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Finance Secretary
Jose Gurria said on Tuesday that the country's financial market
has become more stable and mature, ruling out the possibility of a
new economic crisis due to the change in government next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Gurria made the assurance that
Mexico's stock prices and exchange rate will not fluctuate
drastically with changes in the political arena.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's economy is expected to grow at least 3
percent this year, and the inflation rate would fall to 13 percent
from last year's 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
The finance secretary also expressed confidence in economic
measures adopted by the government, such as the creation of the
Institute for the Protection of Bank Savings and the amendment of
related laws. He said these steps will prevent a new financial
crisis from occurring.
</P>
<P>
In the past 25 years, Mexico's economy has always experienced
sharp slumps whenever a new government was elected. 
</P>
