<HEADLINE> Another Doping Incident Shadows Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Drugs took the place of
sports at the center stage of the 13th Pan Am Games here today as
another titlist tested positive and had her gold medal stripped of.
</P>
<P>
The Dominican high jumper Juana Rosario Arrendel has been
confirmed to fail a drug test after her sample B test also
returned positive.
</P>
<P>
This marked the second doping incident overshadowing the 13th
Pan American Games following the Canadian men's roller hockey
goalie Steve Vezina failed a drug test two days ago.
</P>
<P>
The PASO Executive Committee decided to reward the women's high
jump gold medal to Solange Witteveen of Argentina, the silver
medal to Luciane Dambacher of Brazil and the bronze medal to
Nicole Forrester of Canada.
</P>
<P>
In another decision of the Executive Committee, Ray Martinez,
member of the Mexican baseball team, was taken out of competition
after he refused to receive a drug test following his team's third-
place playoff loss to Canada.
</P>
<P>
Arrendel, only aged at 21, took Estonozolol, an anabolic
steroid which was called "Ben substance" because the disgraced
Canadian sprinter used it, to post a personal best jump of 1.93
meters to grab the country's sole gold medal since the beginning
of the Games.
</P>
<P>
In today's Pan Am Games, Canada's medal torrent in the swimming
pool continued here today as the home favourites repeated
yesterday's hat-trick performances with three more gold (men's
400m medley, women's 200m freestyle and women's 200m breaststroke)
to their credit.
</P>
<P>
F. Sanchez of Venezuela picked up his country's fourth title
during the Games by setting a meet record to win the men's 100m
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
The American men's 4X200m freestyle quartet event saved the day
for the traditional powerhouse, winning their second swimming gold
after ten events had been decided.
</P>
<P>
In total, Cuba had a harvest Tuesday which saw them land four
golds, three silvers and one bronze, the hosts Canada following
closely with a 4-2-3 record.
</P>
<P>
But the United States still topped the medals tally with a
total of 199 medals, 76 of them golds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
