<HEADLINE> Thai Air Force to Order 25 Used Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
confirmed that the cabinet had decided to buy 25 second-hand Alpha
Jets from Germany, Channel 9, Thai state television station
reported on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Chuan, also defense minister, told reporters after a Cabinet
meeting on Tuesday afternoon that the Franco-German Alpha Jets
will replace the aging OV-10s and peace-makers of the Thai air
force which are due to be decommissioned in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year old Alpha Jets, costing one million baht (27,000
U.S. dollars) apiece plus a reconditioning cost of 49 million baht
(1.3 million dollars) per plane, are expected to be delivered in
two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The squadron, costing about 1.2 billion baht (32 million
dollars) in total, will be paid over three years without causing
too great a burden to Thai economy, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai air force initially planned to procure 50 Alpha Jets
from the Luftwaffe for a close air support role to replace the two
aging squadrons of OV-10 and Peace-makers.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister, in light of economic constraints
and concerns about aircraft maintenance in the next 15 years, made
a compromise decision to allow the purchase of 25 used planes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
