<HEADLINE> China Intensifying Construction Work On Large Energy Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China's first major energy
project to join coal mines, a railway, a power station, and a port
is two-thirds of the way through and is expected to be completed
by 2005.
</P>
<P>
The main work of the Shenhua Project is developing the Shenfu
Dongsheng Coalfield in the northern part of Shaanxi Province and
the southern part of Inner Mongolia, the Baotou-Huanghua Railway,
and Huanghua Port, according to an official in charge.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 90-billion yuan project is important for
energy development in central and western China and for ensuring
energy supplies in the eastern and southern parts of China.
</P>
<P>
The Shenfu Dongsheng Coalfield now has an annual production
capacity of 16.8 million tons and the 172-km Baotou-Shenmu Railway
and the 269-km Shenmu-Shuozhou Railway have already been completed.
The Shuozhou-Huanghua Railway is expected to link up with the
Beijing-Kowloon Railway by 2000 and to go on to Huanghua Port by
2002.
</P>
<P>
Work at Huanghua Port is also going smoothly and some 846
million yuan has been spent on its first phase, which involves
nearly 10 million cu.m. of earth and stone. By 2002, the port will
have four 35,000-ton deep-water berths that can handle 30 million
tons of cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
By 2005, the project's annual coal production and shipping
capacity will be 50 million tons, the official says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0252 </DOCNO>
