<HEADLINE> Flood in Eastern Thai Province Alleviated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The situation of the
flood-stricken Thai province of Chantaburi has been improved
substantially and life there is expected to be normal in one or
two days, Channel 9, the state television station, reported here
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Water level in downtown Chantaburi, in eastern Thailand, has
fallen to 30 centimeters on Tuesday from 70 centimeters on Monday
and is still falling.
</P>
<P>
Traffic resumed on major roads in the province and the
displaced people began to return home.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said after Tuesday's cabinet
meeting that every province in the country has been ordered to be
alert to possible floods and prepare emergency relief goods.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology Department predicted that the northeastern and
eastern parts of the country may expect more heavy rains in a few
days.
</P>
<P>
So far, the severe flood in Chantaburi province, which was
described as the worst in a century, has caused roughly 500
million baht (13.5 million U.S. dollars) in damage, according to
an initial estimate by the provincial authorities.
</P>
<P>
Chantaburi province is a major producer of durian and rambutan
and is a trading center for precious stones and gems.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet Tuesday approved an initial budget of 50 million
baht (1.35 million dollars) for the relief operation in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart said that his ministry
would set aside an emergency fund of 100 million baht (2.7 million
dollars) which would be spent at the request of the provincial
governor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
