<HEADLINE> Brazil to Raise Oil Price Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government
announced on Tuesday that it will raise the country's oil prices
for the fifth time this year to keep in line with the
international crude prices and the current dollar prices.
</P>
<P>
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso has insisted that the rise
should not exceed 10 percent despite the prediction of some
specialists that the price hike would be around 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Parente, Minister of Civil Affairs of the Presidency,
told a press conference that the rise will come "in the next few
days", but he specified that the price of diesel fuel will remain
unchanged as the other petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The price of diesel fuel is not to be affected because of an
agreement reached last week to bring an end to the truck drivers'
strike, which practically paralyzed the country for two days.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will have to adjust its oil prices due to a recent
agreement forged with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) under
which it will import at least half its domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
Brazil had lifted its domestic petroleum prices by a total of
47 percent in February, March, April and June, and the figure will
jump to 56 percent with the latest rise.
</P>
<P>
The South American oil consumer imported crude at 9.42 U.S.
dollars a barrel till the end of last year, but this week it has
had to pay almost 20 dollars a barrel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
