<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Filipinos Killed, Many Buried in Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Three children were killed, more
than 25 people were injured and about 100 still missing and feared
buried alive under the debris of their houses in a disastrous
landslide at a mountain side housing area in the northern
Philippines Tuesday night, according to a report of the Philippine
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The report said that tons of earth and gravel rampaged down
into the six-hectare Cherry Hill Subdivision in Antipolo City in
Rizal province shortly after 7 p.m. at the height of a heavy
downpour.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Antipolo City Mayor Angelito Gatlabayan
as saying that more than 50 out of about 400 houses in the
subdivision were destroyed by the landslide.
</P>
<P>
Rainwater accumulated at the top of the mountain flowed down
into the subdivision, apparently softening the ground that held
the foundation of the houses, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Heavy equipment, ambulances and rescue workers have rushed to
the scene. As of 3 a.m. Wednesday, 25 people had been retrieved
from the debris and brought to the district hospital while about
200 survivors were evacuated to a nearby church.
</P>
<P>
Flash floods brought about by torrential rains starting Sunday
hit Metro Manila and nearby provinces, killing at least 28 people,
submerging nearly 270 villages and affecting more than 200,000
people.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada declared Tuesday a state of
calamity in Metro Manila and the provinces of Pangasinan, Pampanga
and Rizal and ordered the release of 440 million pesos (11 million
U.S. dollars) from the calamity fund.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all government agencies to coordinate search,
rescue and relief operations to ensure the safety of the residents
in the affected areas and safeguard the properties of the
residents who abandoned their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
