<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carries a front-page commentary on developing
rural market. It says that China's 900 million rural people make
up the world's largest consumer group, and have the great
possibility to provide China with commercial opportunities.
</P>
<P>
-- A commentator's article further exposes the nature of and
harm done by the Falun Gong cult.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carries a signed article today, further refuting
Lee Teng-hui's splittist remarks.
</P>
<P>
The article by Huang Jiashu says that Lee Teng-hui's "two
states" remarks have neither historical evidence nor a legal basis
to back it, and it will surely bring calamities to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
-- China Tuesday announced some new policies to help State-
owned enterprises (SOEs) shake off difficulties in three years (
1998-2000).
</P>
<P>
Zheng Silin, vice-minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, told a news conference yesterday that seven important
measures must be fully implemented in the second half of the year
in order to realize the objectives of the three-year reform set
for the SOEs.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Sharp increases in the salaries of civil servants should
help spur domestic consumption, said a top financial researcher
yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering increasing salaries of the civil
servants by some 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- China officially released the first Quality Protein Maize (
QPM) hybrid strain - Zhongdan 9409 - yesterday, declaring it a
significant agricultural breakthrough that will ease the country's
increasing food demand in the new millennium. 
</P>
