<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salary Increase to Spur Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Sharp increases in salaries of
civil servants will help spur domestic consumption, according to a
top financial researcher in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Jia Kang, deputy director of Financial Research Institution
under the Ministry of Finance, was quoted by today's China Daily
as saying that the increase will stimulate domestic demand for
consumption in the short term, and perfect the income distribution
system in the long run.
</P>
<P>
Jia also warned the public against unrealistically high
expectations.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the government is considering increasing
salaries of civil servants by some 40 percent, the biggest
increase in history.
</P>
<P>
There are about 10.9 million civil servants in China. If their
monthly wages are increased by an average 120 yuan (about 14.4 U.S.
dollars), the total increase will be an astonishing 16 billion
yuan (about 1.9 billion U.S. dolalrs), the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to judge how much of the increased income will
go into the market even though the country has lowered bank
deposit rates again and again, and some of the restrictive
policies hindering consumption have been cleared," Jia added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
