<HEADLINE> Three Events Named as Backbone in SEA Games Medal Tally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's chef de mission for
the 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games Mochammad Hindarto named
three events as the backbone in the country's efforts to earn as
many gold medals as possible, The Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto named taekwondo, pencak silat and karate as the sports
which had the biggest possibilities to contribute golds for the
contingent, which aims to retain the overall title by winning 70
gold medals.
</P>
<P>
In the SEA Games here two years ago, taekwondo contributed six
golds, karate 14 golds and pencak silat 15 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia and Thailand will fight really hard to retain the
overall title. The medal tally difference will not be really great.
Based on reports from our embassy in Bangkok, Thailand plans to
earn 67 of 235 gold medals on offer," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 67 medals will likely come from swimming (15), boxing (7),
track and field (16), and karate with an estimated seven golds.
</P>
<P>
"If our track and field athletes manage to contest with the
Thais, I believe we can beat them," Hindarto said during the
farewell ceremony on Tuesday to pray for athletes' success in the
biennial event from August 7 to 15.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto also named Malaysia as another threat.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysian athletes competed in last year's Commonwealth Games
and they aim to finish second in the 2001 Games in Kuala Lumpur,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
SEA Games training director Imron ZS said that 452 athletes and
officials would leave on Wednesday on two flights using national
carrier Garuda Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
