<HEADLINE> Canada Keeps Momentum in Pan Am Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada's medal torrent
in the Pan Am Pool continued here today as the home favourites
repeated yesterday's hat trick performances with three more golds
to their credit.
</P>
<P>
F. Sanchez of Venezuela picked up his country's fourth title
during the Games by setting a meet record to win the men's 100m
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
The American men's 4X200m freestyle quartet event saved the day
for the traditional powerhouse, winning their second swimming gold
after ten events had been decided.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Curtis Allen Myden rewrote men's 400m medley Pan Am
record as he swept to victory in four minutes 15.52 seconds,
ripping more than three seconds off the previous old mark of 4:18.
55.
</P>
<P>
American Eric Donnelly finished a well-beaten second at 4:17.86,
with another Canadian Owen Von Richter third at 4:19.62.
</P>
<P>
Jessica Deglau took the women's 200m freestyle event by
clocking 2:00.65, Jamaican J.A. Atkinson placing second in 2:01.11
and American Talor Benel third in 2:03.18.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200m breastroke event, Lauren Van Oosten,
cheered by a delirious sold-out home crowd, beat off strong
American challenges to finish top.
</P>
<P>
Her winning time was 2:30.36, with two Americans A.J.
Mcreynolds and Katie Yevak following closely as the second and
third respectively.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's Sanchez showed his determination to attack the
record from start to finish, touching in 53.33 to shave 0.12
seconds off the old mark set by Nesty Anthony eight years ago in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
In today's last relay event in the Pan Am Pool, the United
States overtook the early pace-setters Canada on the second leg
and never looked behind afterwards, clocking 7:22.29 to win the
gold.
</P>
<P>
Brazil took the silver with a time of 7:22.92, with Canada
wrapping up the day with a bronze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
