<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Serbian Prime Minister Calls for Stable Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of Yugoslavia's
Republic of Serbia Mirko Marjanovic said Tuesday that a stable
economy is the top priority of his government, the official Tanjug
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to the flood-hit Batocina in central Serbia,
Marjanovic said the government would work to stabilize prices and
currency, prevent further falls of living standards, rebuild
homeland and speed up reforms in all fields.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Yugoslavia has managed to maintain in general the
stability of the country's economy and market, despite serious
damages by NATO's air strikes and ongoing pressure from various
aspects.
</P>
<P>
"We are not able to restore in a short time all economic
facilities destroyed in NATO bombings but we can and must do that
in order to ensure the normal functioning of our economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian prime minister said some people are keeping up
pressure on Yugoslavia in an attempt to sabotage efforts to
stabilize the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the Yugoslav and Serbian governments are determined to
march forward along the best road for the people.
</P>
<P>
Above all, the deterioration of the living standards caused by
war must be halted, he said, so the stabilization of prices and
currency is the starting point to map out the country's economic
policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
