<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Strange Hillside" In Northern China Attracts Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A slightly sloping hill in the
suburbs of Shenyang, the capital of Liaoning Province, that can
cause a vehicle to move up it without using the engine has
attracted three million visitors from all over the world in the
past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The 80-meter incline of less than 10 degrees will cause a car
to continue up to the top even if the driver stops the car midway.
It used to be a section of highway, but in 1989, a driver who
happened to stop for a rest there discovered that his truck just
continued on.
</P>
<P>
Some people say that the strange phenomenon is the result of
gravitational or other magnetic force in the area and others
believe that it is just an illusion.
</P>
<P>
But, while the debates continue, local officials and villagers
have put 40 million yuan (8 million U.S. dollars ) into the area
to attract tourists and hope to spend another 30 million yuan on
hotels and entertainment facilities in the next few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
