<HEADLINE> Chinese Drinks Quality Needs Further Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A recent inspection by the State
Quality and Technical Supervision Administration showed that less
than 60 percent of purified bottled water and 29 percent of milk
drinks met the state requirements, according to today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The inspection covered 2,132 types of products collected from
more than 1,800 domestic manufacturers across the country in the
second quarter of this year. About 79.4 percent of these products
proved to be up to standard, up 1.6 percentage points over the
first quarter, said Zhu Mingxuan, the administration's vice-
director.
</P>
<P>
Large State-owned enterprises continued to turn out the
greatest number of reliable products, the inspection found. Some
94 percent of products from large enterprises fulfilled State
requirements, but the figure of small enterprises was only 74
percent, administration statistics indicated.
</P>
<P>
Problems cropped up in the food and beverage industry.
Inadequate protein, vitamin A and calcium content were the major
problems of 22 types of substandard milk drinks, according to the
quality inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
