<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Defying the veto threat by the Clinton
administration, the U.S. House of Representatives approved on
Tuesday a bill that would cut overseas spending and slash funding
for the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The 12.6 billion U.S. dollar foreign operations bill, passed by
a vote of 385 to 35, would decrease the World Bank's lending
program for the world's poorest countries by 232 million dollars
and also cut off aid to foreign groups engaged in abortion-related
services. (U.S.-WB-Funding)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council on
Tuesday authorized the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) to stay
one month longer until September 30.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a council meeting following U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's request for UNAMET's extension last
week. (UN-East Timor)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- The newly announced Canadian cabinet was sworn in as
a mid-term cabinet shuffle completed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The "medium-sized" shuffle brings five new faces to the cabinet
of "continuity and fresh ideas," according to the Prime Minister's
Office.
</P>
<P>
The promotion of former Ontario Health Minister Elinor Caplan
is described by insiders as the most significant addition to the
cabinet. Ms. Caplan replaces Lucienne Robillard as Minister of
Citizenship and Immigration.
</P>
<P>
Many of the cabinet's most prominent ministers stay at their
posts, including Minister of Finance Paul Martin, Minister of
Health Allan Rock, Minister of Foreign Affairs Lloyd Axworthy,
Minister of Transport David Collenette, Minister of Justice Anne
Mclellan and Minister of Industry John Manley. (Canada-Cabinet
Shuffle)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Pentagon alleged on Tuesday that Iraq had
moved more anti-aircraft missiles into the southern no-fly zone,
possibly to enforce its challenge to U.S. and British invading
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon described the move as fitting "a
pattern of Iraqi behavior".
</P>
<P>
The United States has exchanged fires with Iraq nearly 110
times this year when Iraq's anti-aircraft system fired at U.S. and
British planes patrolling the two no-fly zones. (US-Iraq-Missiles)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Tuesday that it will allow
direct charter flights to Cuba from New York and Los Angeles as
part of its "people-to-people contact" policy.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time that direct flights were allowed to
Cuba from these two cities since the U.S. administration imposed
the embargo against Cuba in 1962. (US-Cuba-Flights)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank has released its first tranches to
Russia under its restructured structural adjustment loans, the
bank announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the World Bank's approval of the restructuring of the
second Coal Sector Adjustment Loan (Coal2) and the Social
Protection Adjustment Loan on July 23, and the third Structural
Adjustment Loan (SAL3), the bank disbursed 50 million U.S. dollars
under the Coal2 last Friday, and a further 100 million dollars on
Tuesday under SAL3, a bank statement said. (World Bank-Russia)
</P>
