<HEADLINE> American Sprinter Mitchell Ban Upheld by IAAF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- American sprinter Dennis Mitchell
was suspended for two years on Tuesday after the arbitration panel
of the International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) ruled he
was guilty of a doping offence, according to reports from Monte
Carlo.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF said the 1992 Olympic 100 meters bronze medallist
would be suspended from April 1, 1998 -- the date of the original
test -- to March 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
All performances achieved by Mitchell during that period were
declared void and he will miss this month's world championships in
Seville.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell, 33, was tested at his Florida home and an analysis
showed abnormal levels of the banned hormone testosterone.
</P>
<P>
But an American hearing last December found Mitchell not guilty
of a doping offence and allowed him to continue competing.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF, the world governing body, insisted on an arbitration
hearing for the case. The panel met at the IAAF's Monte Carlo
headquarters last month.
</P>
<P>
"The arbitrators have concluded that "the USATF's doping board
decision of December 12 and 24, 1998, was erroneous," the IAAF
said in Tuesday's statement.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson was given a
hearing by an IAAF special committee over his life ban imposed by
the Canadian athletics federation, an official source said.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year old Johnson provided "new elements" to the
committee as he seeks to return to competition, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Another meeting of the committee is scheduled for August 16.
</P>
<P>
Johnson was stripped of both his Olympic gold medal and his 9.
79 world record in the 100 metres at the 1988 Games in Seoul after
he tested positive for steroids.
</P>
<P>
Five years later, in January 1993, he failed another doping
test after an indoor 60-metres race in Montreal and was banned for
life by the Canadian federation.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in as many years that the U.S.governing
body has been overruled by the IAAF arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
Mary Slaney, the former double world champion at 1,500 and 3,
000 meters, also had an adverse testosterone test after the U.S.
Olympic trials in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The American governing body decided against a suspension but
the IAAF overruled that decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990804.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, New Zealand Sign Agricultural Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and New Zealand signed an
agreement here Tuesday on technical cooperation to help promote
trade in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Brazilian Agriculture Minister
Marcus Vinicius Pratini de Moraes and John Luxton, his New Zealand
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The document specifies the establishment of norms and
procedures for the mutual recognition of national defense systems
related to plant diseases and the certification of products
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the two countries are planning to
exchange information in veterinary, animal health and husbandry
fields, as well as working to check the spread of agricultural
diseases and plagues.
</P>
<P>
Pratini said Brazil would, in the near future, export fruits,
pork and poultry to New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Brazil now exports coffee, sugar and orange juice to New
Zealand, while New Zealand only exports dairy products, especially
powdered milk, to Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
