<HEADLINE> Haze Disrupts Navigation in Malacca Strait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Haze triggered by forest fires in
Indonesia's Riau province last month began disrupting navigation
in the Malacca Strait, Chief of the Riau Office of the Forestry
and Plantation Ministry Darminto Soetono said.
</P>
<P>
"I have received a report that the haze has reduced visibility
in the Malacca Strait," he was quoted by the Antara News Agency
Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He put the blame on slash-and-burn practices for the haze.
</P>
<P>
Since forest and bush fires are rife in Riau during the dry
season, the local forest fire controlling agency has put the
province in Alert I category.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many parts of Riau province have been
covered by haze for nearly one month now and the vapors are
beginning to reduce visibility and irritating people's eyes.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Meteorology and Geophysics Agency in the
provincial capital of Pekanbaru Anwar said weather conditions in
Riau in general and Pekanbaru in particular have become
unfavorable because the haze is getting thicker and thicker.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the satellite, the province had 167
hot spots on July 20, 8 hot spots on July 21 and 543 hot spots on
July 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
