<HEADLINE> IAAF Examines Johnson's Reinstatement Application </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The athletics world ruling body
Tuesday began to examine the reinstatement application of
disgraced Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson who was making his last
bid to return to the field.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian runner and his advisers faced a three-man
subcommittee, led by IAAF General-Secretary Istvan Gyulai, which
will recommend to the body's council whether or not to allow
Johnson back into competition.
</P>
<P>
If the council, which meets in Seville on August 17, rules
against Johnson there will be no possibility of an appeal any more.
</P>
<P>
Johnson was stripped of his Olympic gold medal and 100-meter
world record after testing positive for steroids at the 1988 Seoul
Olympics. He was given a life ban after the second positive test
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
But the sprinter was thrown a life rope this year when Canadian
arbitrator Graeme Mew declared that national athletics authorities
had not made all of the runners' appeal options clear in 1993.
</P>
