<HEADLINE> Export Of Open Coastal City Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Exports and imports in Dalian, a
coastal port city in northeast China's Liaoning Province, were
worth 3.01 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of this year, 7.
9 percent more than for the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Customs officials say that imports were up 7.6 percent
at 1.3 billion U.S. dollars worth, and exports were up 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city's overseas-funded enterprises contributed a great deal
to the growth. Their exports for the period were worth 1.25
billion U.S. dollars, up 13 percent, or accounting for 74 percent
of the city's total. Also, exports to Southeast Asia, the Republic
of Korea, and Japan were up 23 percent and show signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of processed goods has been increasing, with
industrial finished goods, mostly hi-tech and high-added-value
goods, accounting for more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nan Changming, the city's vice-mayor, said that they will try
to increase exports to Latin America and Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
