<HEADLINE> New Zealand Can Learn From Australia: NZ Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Treasurer Bill
English has said as his country is lagging behind Australia in
economic performance, it could learn from the policies of the
Australian government.
</P>
<P>
"We have looked pretty carefully at what they (Australians)
do, and I think we can learn from things they do," the Dominion, a
Wellington-based Newspaper, Wednesday quoted the treasurer as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer, the second most important figure in the Cabinet
just after the prime minister, said the New Zealand government
would look at Australia's experience with tariffs, industry
development and corporate taxation. "Some of those we can learn
from. We're open-minded about that," he said.
</P>
<P>
But English said New Zealanders should take a longer-term view
of their economy rather than dashing across to Australia in
response to a temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
"It's a mistake to generalize from the current circumstances --
either when you're doing better or when you're doing worse. So I
don't go along with the fashionable view that because Australia is
moving faster than us now, New Zealanders should give up and
emigrate," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
