<HEADLINE> Sotomayor Allegedly Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's Javier Sotomayor,
the men's high jump world record holder, reportedly tested
positive in sample A following his gold medal-winning performance
in the 13th Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian national TV network CBC and Radio Canada reported
here today that the Cuban world and Olympic champion was the
latest doping offender, and obviously the most high-profile at the
Winnipeg Games after Steve Vezina, the Canadian men's roller hocky
goaltender, and Juana Rosario Arrendel, Dominican women high
jumper, took the banned drugs.
</P>
<P>
But when asked about the tricky question at a news conference
today, Eduardo de Rose, chairman of the Pan American Sports
Organizaion (PASO) Medical Commission, gave a discreet reply.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to give the name. The case is still under study.
Sample B is in the process of being analyzed.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait until the full confirmation comes out,
otherwise it will be against the PASO regulations."
</P>
<P>
He said the result of Sample B possibly comes out tomorrow.
