<HEADLINE> Dominican High Jumper Confirmed Positive in Sample B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Dominican high
jumper Juana Rosario Arrendel was stripped of the Pan Am gold
medal here today after her sample B test also returned positive.
</P>
<P>
This marked the second doping incident overshadowing the 13th
Pan American Games following the Canadian men's roller hockey
goalie Steve Vezina failed a drug test two days ago.
</P>
<P>
"We're very sad that the Dominican Republic athlete Juana
Rosario Arrendel made a mistake," Mario Vazquez Rana, president of
the Pan American Sports Organization (PASO) said at a news
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The PASO Executive Committee decided to reward the women's high
jump gold medal to Solange Witteveen of Argentina, the silver
medal to Luciane Dambacher of Brazil and the bronze medal to
Nicole Forrester of Canada.
</P>
<P>
In another decision of the Executive Committee, Ray Martinez,
member of the Mexican baseball team, was taken out of competition
after he refused to receive a drug test following his team's third-
place playoff loss to Canada.
</P>
<P>
"We take it as a positive doping because he acted against rules,
" Rana said.
</P>
<P>
Arrendel, only aged at 21, took what was called "Ben substance"
to post a personal best jump of 1.93 meters to grab the country's
sole gold medal since the beginning of the Games.
</P>
<P>
"It is painful to see such a young athlete make such a big
mistake," Dr. Eduardo de Rose, chairman of the PASO Medican
Commission said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the substance Ben Johnson has taken. It's extremely
important for us to know where she got it."
</P>
<P>
Estonozolol, which was found in Arrendel's urine sample, is an
anabolic steroid to increase power in speed, especially in the
competitions of high jump and 100-meter race.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the third athlete whose sample A tested
positive, who was reported by the Canadian TV network CBC and
Radio Canada to be Cuba's world record holder Javier Sotomayor, Dr.
Rosa's gave a discreet reply.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not going to give the name. The case is still under study.
Sample B is in the process of being analyzed.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait until the full confirmation comes out,
otherwise it will be against the PASO regulations."
</P>
<P>
Despite the doping incidents which occupied the headlines
instead of the Pan Am Games itself, Rana declared the Winnipeg
Games is "super clean".
</P>
<P>
There have been over 2000 cases dealt with since the beginning
of the Games, and only two of them turned out positive.
</P>
<P>
Rana continued to argue that there have never been a Pan Am
Games involving less than four positive cases, and it is almost at
the end of the competitions.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very good result," Rana said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
